<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium on Occupational Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international
symposium on occupational health started here today under the
theme: Risk Reduction In the Workplace.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, held for the first time in Africa, was being
attended by over 200 occupational health practitioners from
Europe, Africa, Asia and Americas.
</P>
<P>
It aimed to provide a forum for exchange of information on
methodologies and applications of research on occupational
health.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organisation estimates that 10 million
workers are injured and a further million contract occupational
diseases annually throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
At her opening address, Zimbabwean Minister of Public Service,
Labour and Social Welfare Florence Chitauro said during the past
10 years, an average of 150 occupational diseases have been
recorded annually in Zimbabwe against a background of about
20,000 work-related injuries and 250 fatalities.
</P>
<P>
However, she said Zimbabwe had since reviewed and strengthened
its laws and tripartite systems and built skills that promoted
sound occupational health practice.
</P>
<P>
Chairperson of the Zimbabwe Occupational Health and Safety
Council Rene Loewenson said that globalisation had ushered in
production processes that posed additional health hazards for the
african continent grappling with falling health budgets.
</P>
<P>
she noted that occupational epidemiologists and professionals
in southern Africa faced the difficult task of distinguishing
between ''occupational'' and ''work related'' risks, particularly
in light of the HIV/AIDS pandemic which, in some cases,
threatened to wipe out the entire workforces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
