<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Starts Down to Lowest Level This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Construction of new homes
in the U.S. declined in August to the lowest level this year, U.S.
Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that housing starts fell by 4.8 percent to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.36 million, the lowest
level since last December.
</P>
<P>
It was also the third decrease in the past four months and the
sharpest since a 5.5 decline in April.
</P>
<P>
The report said that housing starts of single-family homes last
month fell by 5 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
1.07 million, the sharpest drop in five months. Apartment building
declined by 4.3 percent to a rate of 291,000.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the starts plunged 19.2 percent in the Northeast --
the largest drop since February. They also fell 3.8 percent in the
West, 3.5 percent in the Midwest and 2.7 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, housing starts in the U.S. are running 4
percent below last year's pace, when they hit an eight-year high
of 1.48 million.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said strong demand for housing, fueled by plentiful
jobs and low mortgage rates, would almost certainly revive home
building from August's level, although not past last year's
record.
</P>
<P>
However, applications for building permits -- a barometer of
future building plans -- fell nationally by 1.6 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.39 million in August. They
fell for both single-family homes and apartments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
