<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean President May Release Predecessors Before Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam is likely to give special pardon to jailed former
presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo before the December
election, a high-ranking government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Kim has maintained a position of pardoning Chun and Roh at an
appropriate time after the presidential election, but it is highly
likely that he will grant the amnesty before the presidential
election as a result of Kyonggi Governor Rhee In-je's entry into
the race last week, the official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rhee announced last Saturday his intention to bolt from the
ruling New Korea Party and run into the election on his own, thus
forcing the ruling party and its presidential candidate Lee
Hoi-chang to face difficulties in the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The president said earlier this month that pardon for Chun and
Roh is a grave issue which should not be resolved by political
considerations.
</P>
<P>
However, the source added that the possibility of Kim moving up
the timing of the special pardon cannot be ruled out in the light
of the need to facilitate unity of all political forces in the
ruling camp under Lee's leadership.
</P>
<P>
The latest opinion polls show Lee and Rhee lagged behind
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung, who is making his fourth bid for
the presidency at his 70s.
</P>
<P>
The special pardon would be a wooing gesture to Kyongsang
Province voters, the home town of the two presidents, in the
forthcoming presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
