<HEADLINE> Delinquency Rate on Credit Cards Increases in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of Americans
overdue on their credit-card bills increased sharply during the
April-June quarter after falling a bit in the first quarter, the
American Bankers Association (ABA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The delinquency rate -- the percentage of accounts 30 or more
days overdue -- was up to a seasonally adjusted 3.69 percent in
the second quarter from 3.51 percent in the previous three months,
the ABA report said.
</P>
<P>
It was near the all-time record of 3.72 percent set during the
last three months of 1996, comparing with the 2.56 percent three
year ago.
</P>
<P>
The sharp increase in consumers falling behind on credit-card
bills has coincided with an explosion in personal bankruptcies,
which reached a record 1.26 million during the 12 months ended
June 30.
</P>
<P>
But based on total dollars outstanding, rather than the number
of accounts, delinquencies dropped to 5.24 percent in the second
quarter from 5.43 percent in the first.
</P>
<P>
The ABA said that bank lenders have been tightening credit
standards during the past year and a half.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a composite delinquency rate for a variety of
closed-end consumer loans -- as opposed to open-ended credit such
as credit cards and home equity loans -- also increased to 2.55
percent in the second quarter, driven by an increase in auto loan
delinquencies. That's up from 2.47 percent in the previous quarter
and the highest in five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
