<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch GDP to Expand in 1997: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of the Netherlands will grow by 3.25 percent this year, the
same as in 1996, said an official report.
</P>
<P>
The growth, according to the latest quarterly report published
by the Netherlands' Central Planning Bureau, is the result of a
robust economic expansion and subdued inflation.
</P>
<P>
The underlying indicators are actually more encouraging,
suggesting a growth rate of 3.75 percent, a figure projected for
next year, the government agency said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Though the U.S. dollar and pound sterling have appreciated
strongly this year, it said, fierce competition on the domestic
market and efficiency improvements are keeping inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
The trend in labor costs remains moderate, opening the way for
further rises in company earnings, and the current 2 percent
annual employment growth is likely to be sustained, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
