<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Jobless Figures Slide to 17-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) - Unemployment figure in Britain
fell by 48,600 last month to their lowest total for 17 years,
according to official figures released here today.
</P>
<P>
The Office For National Statistics said the number of people
out of work and claiming unemployment benefit dropped to
1,496,600, giving a jobless rate of 5.3% of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
It was the 18th consecutive fall in the seasonally adjusted
total, which is now at its lowest level since 1980.
</P>
<P>
Another main component of the day's statistics was average
earnings. Underlying earnings grew by 4.5% in the year to July, up
from 4.25% the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government said the unemployment and earnings data
triggered to inflationary alarm bells.
</P>
<P>
However, employment minister Andrew Smith was quoted as saying
that "There is no room for complacency... but it would be wrong to
draw alarm signals from the unemployment figures today."
</P>
<P>
"I believe today's numbers are consistent with the sustainable
growth that the UK government figure is determined to achieve," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
