<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Germans Killed in Cairo's Terrorist Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Suspected Muslim militants
attacked a bus in the busiest quarter of downtown Cairo at noon
today, killing nine German tourists.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Rahian Shehata, Governor of Cairo told reporters that
nine foreign tourists were also injured when three attackers
opened fire and threw some bombs into a parked tourist bus in
front of the Egyptian Antiquities Museum.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to Kasr al-Eini Hospital for treatment,
he said, adding that the attack was timed to create the utmost
upheaval as the place it targeted was the world famous trove of
Pharaonic treasures sitting on the edge of Taharir Square, Cairo's
most crowded commercial and business center.
</P>
<P>
As the first bomb went off, at least 33 tourists were inside
the bus. The white bus was gutted black and its glass windows were
all broken.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists, shocked and some sobbed, were ushered away
from the museum, one of Egypt's most famous tourist attraction and
usually heavily-guarded.
</P>
<P>
An Australian, identified herself as Laura, told Xinhua that
the police and the attackers exchanged fire. "Just minutes,
explosions, fire, bullets, and hell... I was waiting at the gate
for others to come out (of the museum)."
</P>
<P>
A police officer, told reporters that two of the attackers,
identified as Saber Mahmoud Farahat Abul Ela and his brother
Mahmoud were wounded and arrested, while the third fled the scene.
</P>
<P>
The police, carrying riot shields and automatic rifles, has
cordoned off the roads leading to the Taharir Square, the city's
central transit point, leading to a near paralysis of the
transportation in adjoining neighborhoods for hours.
</P>
<P>
The area is being combed in hunt for any of their cohorts and
to secure it from any further possible bomb threats, according to
the police.
</P>
<P>
A police officer, on condition of anonymity, said that the
attackers were wearing business suits in an apparent attempt to
avoid attention in the super-crowded city center that hosts a
number of government offices and plush hotels.
</P>
<P>
Cairo Security Chief Major General Mohamed Abdel Latif said
that the assailants were immediately overpowered by the museum's
security guards after the explosions.
</P>
<P>
Today's bomb attack was the latest in a five-year violent
campaign launched by Muslim militants since 1992 to overthrow the
secular government and install a strict Islamic rule in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,200 people have been killed in the violence, including
tourists, police officers and Coptic Christians. Most of the
attacks took place in Upper Egypt, hideouts for most militants.
</P>
<P>
It is suspected that the attack was launched to retaliate
against the country's single largest trial of 98 Muslim militants
three days ago.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian military tribunal condemned to death and hanged
four Muslims and meted out various prison terms to 69 others
convicted of staging major terrorist attacks to topple the
government.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack on foreigners, Muslim militants opened
fire on a group of Greek tourists in Cairo's Europa Hotel in April
1996, killing 18 and injuring 16.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been the largest tourist exporting country to
Egypt. A total of 460,000 Germans visited Egypt in 1996. 
</P>
