<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Strengthen UN Role in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to further strengthen the role of the
United Nations in Somalia by adding another professional staff
member to the United Nations Political Office for Somalia(UNPOS)
and convening an ambassador-level meeting on Somalia.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said developments
since the Nairobe understanding and the Sodere declarations, the
agreements reached in Mogadishu and the Sana'a and Cairo
agreements, had given rise to hope that the Somalia parties might
have finally arrived at a stage where they would engage in serious
consultations for peace.
</P>
<P>
Annan recommended to hold a meeting on Somalia at the
ambassador level at Headquarters in September, 1997, chaired by
the Under-Secretary-General of the Department of Political
Affairs, which would aim at harmonizing views on mechanism and
measures to maximize the international community's efforts to help
Somalia achieve national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the U.N. chief also proposed to adding another
professional staff member to the UNPOS.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the political process in Somalia was at another
critical juncture and the international community would continue
to make every effort to help Somalia people in the relief,
rehabilitation, reconstruction and development fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
