<HEADLINE> U.S. Credit Card Delinquencies Near Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Credit card delinquencies in
U.S. jumped to 3.69 percent of accounts in the second quarter,
according to a new report by the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
That's second only to the 3.72 percent recorded in the fourth
quarter of 1996, the ABA said.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcies that too often follow credit card
delinquencies are taking a toll on all card users. Card issuers
raise interest rates and fees to try to recoup losses.
</P>
<P>
The ABA said banks have tightened credit standards. But some
experts said they haven't done enough to keep a good control. Many
platinum cards offer 100,000 U.S. dollar credit lines.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, outstanding card credit totaled 1.8
trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Card issuers could stem rising delinquencies by shrinking
credit lines and terminating inactive accounts, experts say.


nnnn
23:29 23:29 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
