<HEADLINE> French FM: Outsiders Cannot Help Solve Algeria's Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine today said he believed that no outsider can offer a
solution to the five-year-old conflict in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
"I say it with much sadness... no one is capable of bringing a
satisfying answer to the Algerian tragedy," Vedrine said. France
is Algeria's former colonial power and its largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine's remarks came after the United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan offered to mediate between the
Algerian government and Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Annan's offer was rejected by the Algerian government, which
called it an interference into the country's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Muslim fundamentalists have been battling the authorities since
early 1992, when the government canceled a general election in
which radical Islamists were on the verge of a victory.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 people have been killed in the violence
thereafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
