<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sight Restoration Program in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A team of ophthalmologists
specializing in cataract surgery have arrived in Gongbo'gyamda
County in southeastern Tibet to launch today a Sight Restoration
Program sponsored in part by the Beijing-based Red Cross
Foundation of China.
</P>
<P>
Herdswoman Jiji, 63, was the first of some 200 patients to
queue at the Gongbo'gyamda People's Hospital. The team performed
eight surgical procedures this afternoon alone.
</P>
<P>
Gongjue, the elderly woman's son-in-law, noted that they had
traveled over 100 km by horseback. "My mother-in-law has suffered
loss of vision due to cataracts for over eight years," said
Gongjue. "We came here upon hearing that Beijing was sending a
high-level medical team to perform free cataract surgery."
</P>
<P>
Liu Ping, who performed the 30 minute surgical procedure on
Jiji, said her vision is to be restored withing two days. Liu said
that state-of-the-art ultrasonic emulsifiers were being used to
implant artificial crystals, a technique being used for the first
time ever in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Following the operation, Jiji told her son-in-law that "The
doctor from Beijing has brought me good luck, and now I will be
able to once again see my ten children and grandchildren."
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute Tibet's high incidence of cataracts,
one of the highest in the nation, to the strong ultraviolet rays
on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau. Some 600 of 5,000 Tibetans currently
suffering from cataracts will undergo surgery as part of the Red
Cross Foundation program.
</P>
<P>
Another team of ophthalmologists left Lhasa today for Nagarze
County in Shannan Prefecture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
