<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Turns Worse in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The haze situation in
Singapore worsened this evening with the three-hourly Pollutant
Standards Index (PSI) reading hitting an all-time high of 226 at
10 p.m., the Environment Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the PSI reading of 226 was higher than the
previous high of 154 recorded at 7 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
"There has been an increase in the intensity of the haze," it
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The ministry advised the elderly and those with heart and
respiratory problems to stay indoors and avoid physical exertion.
</P>
<P>
The day started fairly clear but the haze got thicker as the
day wore on. At 4 p.m., the three-hourly PSI reading was 122 while
the 24-hour reading stood at 70, still within the moderate range.
</P>
<P>
However, at 7 p.m., the three-hourly reading rose to 154, a
level described by the Environment Ministry as "poor." The
situation got worse at 10 p.m., with the PSI reading reaching the
record high level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
