<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Securities Brokerage Raided Over Payoff Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's third biggest
securities brokerage was raided by prosecutors and the country's
securities watchdog today over payoffs to a corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office and the Securities
and Exchange Surveillance Commission suspect that, by making the
payoffs, Daiwa Securities Co. violated Japan's Commercial Code.
</P>
<P>
Investigators alleged that Daiwa officials in 1995 extended
over 67 million yen (560,000 U.S. dollars) to Ryuichi Koike, a
corporate racketeer, or "sokaiya" in Japanese, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Daiwa also allegedly complied a demand by Koike to compensate
investment losses of 300 million yen (2.5 million dollars) in his
illegal discretionary stock transactions beginning in August 1992.
</P>
<P>
The compensation, said the sources close to the investigation,
was in violation of the Securities and Exchange Law.
</P>
<P>
In their operation today, prosecutors searched several Daiwa
facilities including its head office, and homes of its executives.
</P>
<P>
It came a day after the arrest of five former and current
executives of Yamaichi Securities Co., the smallest of Japan's
"Big Four" securities brokerages, for extending payoffs to Koike.
</P>
<P>
Koike, already in custody and indicted in a similar payoff
scandal involving Japan's biggest brokerage Nomura Securities
Co. and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, was served a fresh arrest warrant
Wednesday on suspicion of the Yamaichi payoff.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors are also reportedly investigating allegations that
Nikko Securities Co., the remainder of the "Big Four," has given
payoffs of up to 10 million yen (83,000 dollars) to Koike.
</P>
<P>
Payoffs to "sokaiya" are banned under the Commercial Code, and
reimbursing stock transaction loss and discretionary securities
trading are illegal under the Securities and Exchange Law.
</P>
<P>
However, the financial institutions find it very difficult to
cut off ties with corporate racketeers like Koike, who can
determine the businesses of these institutions by possessing large
amount of their shares through illegal means.
</P>
<P>
Eight top executive of Daiwa will soon resign to take
responsibility for the payoff scandal, and Nikko is also likely to
drastically reshuffle its top management, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
