<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Round of Economic Restructuring Expected in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Marked by a proposition of
diversified forms to realize public ownership, China is brewing up
a strategic restructuring of state-owned enterprises in a deeper sense,
so as to basically establish a system of socialist market
economy by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
In this course China's economic restructuring as a whole is
expected to do deeper.
</P>
<P>
"China is targeting at the most formidable block, the reforms
of state-owned enterprises, on its way to economic restructuring,"
said Professor Gao Shangquan, vice president with the China
Society for Economic Restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Theoretical breakthroughs concerning the connotation of public
ownership, manifestations of its dominant position in the
national economy, and diversified forms of
public ownership in the report delivered by Jiang Zemin at the
National Congress of the Communist Party which was just ended
earlier today, will lend a powerful impetus to a
new round of economic reform, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
His report indicated that any ownership forms in accordance with
"the three favorables" -- favorable to promoting the productive
forces in a socialist society, increasing the overall strength of
the socialist state and raising the people's living standards,
can be employed.
</P>
<P>
These remarks, it is widely believed, have laid a theoretical
foundation for breakthroughs to be scored in economic
restructuring, state-owned enterprises in particular.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of Prof. Gao, the forthcoming economic
restructuring will be characterized by an improved structure of
ownership, a shrink in the number of the state businesses but
a higher efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Gao added, enterprises will effectively
become the main subject of the market competition, capital flow
will be facilitated, and the role of government will be
transformed to indirect control of the enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
