<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Round of Economic Restructuring Expected in China-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While strengthening development of 1,000 large-and medium-sized
enterprises which have a bearing on the national economy, China
will allow a great number of state-owned enterprises to gear to
market operation, encouraging them to run in any forms of
organization such as the systems of joint stock and joint stock
partnership so as to invigorate the state sector as a whole and
make the state-owned sector to supplement each other with the
non-state-owned sector for a common development.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the state-owned enterprises has been deemed as the
key in structural reform.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics have shown that China has 300,000
state-owned enterprises, 13,000 of which are large-and
medium-sized ones. Some are in a difficult position as a result of
an inflexible mechanism, posing a trouble for the sustained and
sound economic development in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, Minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission, said the state will make a breakthrough in the
reform of state-owned enterprises in terms of five aspects
including innovation of systems, structural readjustment,
strategic reorganization of the national economy, "emphasizing the
bigger enterprises while giving a free reign to smaller ones", and
merger and bankruptcy of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to build basically a modern enterprise system in the
majority of key large- and medium-sized enterprises, with marked
improvement in their performance, he added.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to push forward development of joint
stock system at state-owned enterprises, improve capital market,
lower the debt ratio and expand the capital fund of enterprises
by raising funds on the capital market.
</P>
<P>
With deepening of reforms in the micro-economy centered around
the improvement of the state-owned enterprises, some economists
held, the macro-economic reforms in such fields as investment,
finance and social security will be further accelerated as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
