<HEADLINE> 15th National Party Congress Elects New Central Committee (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) closed here this morning after
electing a new CPC Central Committee with 193 members and 151
alternate members, and a new Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection (CCDI) with 115 members.
</P>
<P>
One of the major tasks of the 15th National Party Congress is
to elect a new CPC Central Committee and a new CCDI.
</P>
<P>
The previous CPC Central Committee had attached great
importance to the the work of personnel arrangement of the current
congress, stressing that the nomination of candidates of the new
Central Committee and the new CCDI should be carried out by giving
full play to inner-Party democracy and the mass line so as to
elect those comrades who are politically sound, have won
outstanding achievements in their jobs and enjoy high reputation
among the masses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the previous Central Committee had also formulated
the democratic procedure for recommendation, scrutiny and
nomination of candidates of the new CPC Central Committee and
the new CCDI.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the requirements of the previous Central
Committee, party organizations of all provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities as well as all departments
under the Party Central Committee and the State Council and all
central institutions of the Army started in August 1996 to
discuss, recommend and scrutinize the candidates of the new CPC
Central Committee and the new CCDI.
</P>
<P>
Over 16,000 Party members across the country have participated
in the democratic recommendation, and the scrutiny group had talks
with 12,000 people separately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15th National Party Congress Elects New Central Committee (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the new committee, other leading officials and outstanding
figures from various fields number 41, including leading officials
and experts from large and medium-sized enterprises, colleges,
universities and research institutes, as well as model workers at
the grassroots level.
</P>
<P>
The committee comprises 38 cadres of ethnic minorities and 25
female cadres, both registering an increase over that of the
previous committee.
</P>
<P>
The education level of the new Central Committee members has
been improved markably. The number of those who have an
educational background of college level or above reaches 318, or
92.4 percent of the total members and alternate members. This
represents a nine percentage points rise from that of the previous
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that members of the newly-elected CPC Central
Commission for Discipline Inspection are mostly persons in charge
of provincial level commissions for discipline inspection, and
leading officials in other fields.
</P>
<P>
The age pattern of the CCDI is improved, with those below 55
years of age accounting for nearly half of the total.
</P>
<P>
The education level of the new commission members has been
fairly improved, with 89.6 percent of them having an educational
background of college level or above.
</P>
<P>
Cadres of ethnic minorities and female members have taken up a
certain proportion in the commission.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected commission is expected to guide the work of
discipline inspection across the country, and play an important
role in guaranteeing the unity of the Party, tightening Party
discipline, maintaining the purity of the Party, intensifying
fight against corruption, improving the Party's style of work and
building a clean and honest government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
