<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on US, Britain not to Block Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq called on U.S. and
Britain to stop obstructing the approval of contracts signed by
Iraq with foreign companies, Iraq News Agency (INA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a message forwarded by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf to U.N. Security Council which was published by INA
today, the minister underlined the necessity of maintaining a
balance between selling Iraqi oil and supplying Iraq with food and
medicines in implementation of the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 986.
</P>
<P>
"Though more than 100 days have passed by since the first stage
of the oil-for-food deal expired, there are still 60 contracts
have not been submitted to the U.N. Sanctions Committee," he said,
adding that more than 70 contracts were suspended at the request
of the U.S. and Britain and 21 contracts were disapproved by the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The message said that that the credibility of the U.N. Security
Council, especially that of the U.S. is questionable. It demands
balance between selling Iraqi oil and supplying it with food and
medicines and the issue should be addressed in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Iraq declared to have its oil exports suspended in June to
protest against U.N. tardiness in approving the contracts signed
by Iraq with foreign companies, as well as the role played by the
U.S. in this connection.
</P>
<P>
U.N. and Iraq signed the oil-for-food deal in May 1996 which
allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over a
six month period to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
goods for its people who are suffering under U.N.-imposed sanction
against Iraq following Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The
U.N. renewed another six months period of the deal on June 4, which
allows Iraq to sell 2 billion dollars of oil as of June 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
