<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loan to Finance Thai Rural Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) said today it has approved a 200 million U.S. dollar loan to
help Thailand finance its rural enterprises to improve rural house
incomes.
</P>
<P>
The loan is part of the bank's 1.2 billion dollar assistance
package announced by the Manila-based financial body to support
the country's economic stabilization program.
</P>
<P>
Because of an overheated property sector and some serious
problems in the banking system, Thailand has been hit by a
prolonged financial crisis since February this year.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has committed to help bail Thailand out of the current
crisis along with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and some
countries.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to finance 54,000 rural enterprises in
the country under a rural enterprise credit project, the ADB said
in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to create 127,000 full-time jobs in the
country's poorest provinces, which are particularly vulnerable to
Thailand's current macroeconomic difficulties, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The project will also strengthen its executing agency, the
state-owned Bank for Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives, in
loan processing, supervision and customer services.
</P>
<P>
Despite Thailand's rapid economic growth in recent years,
household incomes in rural areas are only a quarter of those in
urban areas, mainly because of low agricultural productivity and a
lack of employment opportunities, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be from the ADB's ordinary capital resources,
with interest to be determined in accordance with the bank's
pool-based variable lending rate system for U.S. dollar loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
