<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over One Seventh of EU Workers Happy With Part-Time Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- About 15 percent of the
employed people in the 15-member European Union (EU) say they are
happy with working on part-time basis.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of the part-timers aged 25 or over say they
don't want to have a full-time job, shows a poll by Eurostat, the
EU's statistical office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Part-time jobs appear to be most prevalent in the Netherlands
engaging 38 percent of the respondents while it is least so in
Greece involving only five percent of those surveyed.
</P>
<P>
"Part-time work is often seen as a policy measure to increase
the number of employed persons by promoting work-sharing,"
explains the Eurostat report summarizing the poll results.
</P>
<P>
For businesses, it says, part-time jobs can be an efficient
tool to respond to peaks in demand for goods and services in a
particular period or to extend the opening hours.
</P>
<P>
"Finally, part-time work meets the specific conditions...for
people who like to combine it with an education or their family
care," according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
