<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Denies Plan to Suspend Talks With Leftists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
today denied planning to terminate its on-going fruitless peace
negotiations with the National Democratic Front (NDF), a leftist
alliance led by the Communist Party of the Philippines (CPP).
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Howard Dee, chief negotiator in the talks with
the NDF, said the government has no plans or intentions to suspend
the three-year-long peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Dee was reacting to reports that the NDF has threatened to stop
negotiating with the government due to continuous military and
police offensives against its military arm, the New People's Army
(NPA).
</P>
<P>
"We have no such intentions and we have just sent a new
schedule of talks to the NDF that would allow both sides to
complete the negotiations by March 1998," Dee said.
</P>
<P>
But Dee failed to confirm whether the government received the
NDF warning of withdrawal from the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Dee admitted that the talks are in a difficult stage as the NDF
has rejected the government's reformulated draft of a
comprehensive agreement on human rights and international
humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered to come up with a revised draft of
the human rights and international humanitarian agreement that
could be more acceptable to the NDF, Dee said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF has fought the government for decades since its
establishment by the CPP in 1969. The military estimated that the
group has about 6,300 armed men currently, a sharp reduction from
more than 10,000 in the 1980s due to intensified military
crackdown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
