<HEADLINE> Beijing Man Begins 1,500-km Trek to Mark Sept. 18th Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing resident Jia
Yuanliang, 33, left Shenyang, capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province, toady on a 1,500-km trek to mark the September
18th Incident.
</P>
<P>
Jia will walk 20 km per day and expects to reach Nanjing,
capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, in 86 days.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six years ago, on September 18th, the Japanese
bombardment of a railway section in Shenyang heralded the
beginning of Japan's military invasion of China.
</P>
<P>
Jia plans to arrive in Nanjing on December 13, the 60th
anniversary of the bloody "Nanjing Massacre".
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops captured the city in the winter of 1937 and
perpetrated a six-week massacre which led to the death of over
300,000 Chinese civilians and unarmed soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"My goal is to ensure that people will never forget the history
of Japanese aggression," said Jia, adding that he hopes for a
world of peace and generations of friendship between the Chinese
and the Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
Jia resigned his well-paying job with a foreign-funded
enterprise and began preparing for the trek one year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
