<HEADLINE> ADB Gives Loan to Pakistan for Wastewater Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) today approved a 70 million U.S. dollar loan to Pakistan to
help it build a sewage treatment plant and system in its southern
industrial city of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Because of toxic effluents discharged by many tanneries and
garment dyeing factories, Karachi has become one of the most
polluted areas in the country, the Manila-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
The wastewater treatment project will build a plant with a
capacity to treat 120,000 cubic meters of sewage a day and
construct and rehabilitate 125 kilometers of sewers.
</P>
<P>
The loan, which will come from the bank's Special Funds
resources, is interest-free and carries a service charge of 1
percent per annum. 
</P>
