<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Implements Nutrition Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government is
implementing an integrated nutrition project throughout the
country for reducing chronic malnutrition among the people.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to contribute significantly toward
reduction of infant and maternal mortality and bring about a
sustainable behavioral change in food intake pattern and caring
practices, government sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition is a serious problem in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five percent of children under five years old are
severely or moderately malnourished while 35 to 50 percent of new
born babies are below normal weight (less than 2,500 grams) and
about 70 percent of mothers and children suffer from
iron-deficiency anemia, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence of night blindness due to vitamin A deficiency
is 17 percent and iodine deficiency disorders affect 47 percent of
the people, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The causes of malnutrition have been identified as inadequate
food intake, poor health and bad feeding and eating practices, the
sources added.
</P>
<P>
The strategies adopted by the government for solving the issues
include accelerating formulation of a national nutrition program,
developing national expertise and capacity to control
malnutrition, strengthening existing nutrition activities and
establishing community-based nutrition interventions in a phased
manner, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Urged to Buy More Food From ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Federation of
Malaysia Consumer Associations (FOMCA) today urged the country to
import more food from fellow ASEAN countries following the
depreciation of its currency ringgit to check the current account
deficit.
</P>
<P>
FOMCA President Hamdan Adnan said a substantial portion of the
country's annual food import bill of over 8 billion ringgit (about
2.6 billion U.S. dollars) was due to imports from the advanced
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The weakening ringgit should prompt the government to buy more
foodstuff from ASEAN countries besides increasing local food
production," he was quoted by the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit has depreciated 20 percent against the U.S. dollar
since early July this year, with the exchange rate today closing
at 3.013/6, compared with 2.5 in early July.
</P>
<P>
Hamdan said neighboring ASEAN member countries like Indonesia,
the Philippines, Vietnam and Myanmar are producers of agricultural
products, from which Malaysia could import.
</P>
<P>
Regretting that "Malaysia's massive dependence on food imports
is due to the absence of an aggressive food production policy." he
said, "The strategy of increasing the price of agricultural
produce to increase farmer's income is not a sound one because it
only leads to inflation." "A better policy would be to make the
farmers increase their production."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysian Energy, Telecommunications and Posts
Minister Leo Moggie said today that the currency crisis faced by
Southeast Asian countries has made Malaysia 20 percent "poorer"
vis-a-vis its earlier financial standing.
</P>
<P>
Hence, he said, the country's industrial sector must buck up to
boost product quality to compete in the international market and
also draw up strategies for its goods to penetrate into new
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
