<HEADLINE> World Economic Development Congress Ends in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Six Annual World
Economic Development Congress, which is of significant relevance
to global infrastructure development in Asian economies, ended
here this evening after three days of wide-ranging discussions
among the international business community.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 delegates from around the world, including some
100 government ministers and senior ministerial representatives
from 80 countries, attended dozens of seminars held simultaneously
in different rooms in five nearby hotels.
</P>
<P>
They offered ideas and views from varied perspective on topics
such as private investment in power industry, global
telecommunications, transportation, water supply and waste water
treatment, logistics and distribution, pharmaceuticals and health
care.
</P>
<P>
Keynote speakers included Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region of China Tung Chee Hwa, former U.S.
secretary of state George Shultz and Nobel Laureate and Economist
Milton Friedman.
</P>
<P>
The World Economic Development Congress was established in 1992
 as a forum for the public and private sectors to interact and
discuss economic issues facing the world. The congress is usually
held immediately preceding the International Monetary Fund and
World Bank Annual Meetings.
</P>
<P>
The congress will meet in Washington, DC, in 1998 and 1999, and
the Czech Republic in the year 2000. 
</P>
