<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Chad to Co-build Road, Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Nhgeria and Chad have agreed
to jointly build direct highway and power links to promote
greater!economic development.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the end of a three-day ministerial
meeting in the Nigerian capital of Abuja on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A communique of the meeting said the ministers had agreed "on
the options and the alternatives to be taken to actualize the
construction of direct highway and power links" between the two
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Details of the projects were not revealed, but Nigeria's
Minister of Works and Housing, Major-general Abdulkarim Adisa
said at the opening of the talks on Monday they might include a
964 million U.S. Dollars road and a 227 million Dollars power
transmission line.
</P>
<P>
According to Adisa, the main objective of building the road
link is to foster better relationship through free movement of
people between the two countries and strengthen bilateral trade
without hindrance or obstacle.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Chad are linked by the Trans-Saharan International
Route via Cameroun. At present, portions of the route are tarred,
but most of the 75-km road remains a dust road, seriously
hampering movement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A team of engineers from the two countries has been formed to
explore a route through Lake Chad, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
A 330-KV single circuit line and a sub-station will also be
built to send electricity from Nigeria to an industrial layout to
be situated along the Nigeria-Chad border.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary studies ildicated the power project is expected to
take three years to complete. 
</P>
</TEXT>
