<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Help Deaf Kids to Speak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese public has long
taken it for granted that a deaf person is automatically
mute. But doctors here are trying to change the misperception by
teaching deaf kids to talk.
</P>
<P>
China has some 17 million people with hearing and speaking
deficiencies, accounting for 28 percent of the country's disabled
population. Of the deaf-mutes, about 740,000 are children under
age six, and the group is expanding by 20,000 to 40,000 youngsters
yearly.
</P>
<P>
Doctors here believe that a deaf child has the ability to
speak, provided he or she wears a hearing aid during early
childhood to pick up language and has a caring home environment.
</P>
<P>
With donations of three million yuan and some special medical
equipment, the China Hearing Medical Science Development Fund
launched "mobile hospitals" last year to provide free hearing
checks to children in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, the roving hospitals have toured over 20
poor counties in Hebei, Shandong, Anhui, Shaanxi and Jiangxi
provinces, and diagnosed some 1,000 kids with hearing problems.
</P>
<P>
In Tongchan County, Shaanxi Province, doctors distributed
hearing aids to deaf children under six who have weak
hearing. Some of them regained their ability to speak properly
after training.
</P>
<P>
Doctors caution the public, pregnant women in poor rural areas
in particular, to be very careful about use of antibiotic
medications, which is believed to be one of the main causes of
congenital deafness.
</P>
<P>
They also volunteer to go to the countryside and give hearing
check-ups to children, and also to give language training courses
to professionals who will teach deaf children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
