<HEADLINE> Daiwa Suspended From Australia's Telstra Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
today suspended Daiwa Securities, the Asian lead manager of the
float of Australia's leading telecommunications company Telstra,
from its role following corruption investigation in Japan.
</P>
<P>
But Australian Finance Minister John Fahey said he remained
confident that the float is on track for November, the Australian
Associated press (AAP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Daiwa Securities, Japan's second largest stockbroker and lead
manager of the 7.2 billion U.S. dollar Telstra float for the
jurisdiction outside the United States and Europe, was last week
reportedly banned from selling shares in Japan," AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese public prosecutors today raided the headquarters of
Daiwa in Tokyo following reports that eight top executives were
about to resign for their role in a widening pay-off scandal.
</P>
<P>
Fahey said Daiwa would be suspended from its role as of
September 19 pending further advice and information.
</P>
<P>
He said the move would protect public confidence in the process
as the critical stage of the Telstra sale approaches.
</P>
<P>
"The government is on track for a November listing of the
shares," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government would appoint an additional lead manager to the
selling syndicate in the Telstra public share offer, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government announced earlier this year a
decision to privatize one-third of Telstra, the largest
telecommunications company in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
