<HEADLINE> Beef Supply Urged in Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Vice Prime
Minister Gilbert Tsoungui has recommended that the supply of beef
be increased in urban centers to bring down prices.
</P>
<P>
The vice prime minister made the statement in Yaounde
Wednesday while presiding over deliberations at the first
semester conference of governors for the 1997/98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to a paper represented by Edmond Mbio, the
secretary of state in charge of industrial and commercial
development on the supply of cattle and beef markets in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The vice prime minister advised the competent services
concerned to regroup graziers in larger vaccination zones so that
a greater quantity of healthy cattle can be transported to urban
centers.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the vice prime minister's recommendation, Mbio
attributed the shortage of beef and cattle to the lack of
transport facilities from high grazing areas to urban centers.
</P>
<P>
Mbio also cited insecurity along the roads from the north to
the south, abusive control by some administrative services and
exportation to neighboring countries for higher profits as some
of the factors leading to the beef shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
