<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Fell to New Record Low Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency of
peso hit a new record low today, plummeting by 3.3 percent to
average at 33.85 pesos to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine Dealing System, the peso opened at 32.36
pesos to one dollar and fell to a record low of 34.05 pesos in the
first few minutes.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first time that the currency breached the level
of 34 pesos to one dollar. The peso is now 28 percent below its
pre-depreciation average of 26.40 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson blamed
political uncertainty for the woes of the peso.
</P>
<P>
"We more or less followed the region," he told reporters,
referring to the prolonged Southeast Asian currency crisis, in
which the Thai baht, the Malaysian ringgit, the Indonesian rupiah,
the Singaporean dollar and the Philippine peso all once tumbled to
record lows.
</P>
<P>
However, the political unstability arising from the Charter
change moves seeking a second term for President Fidel Ramos
brought more jitters to the foreign exchange market, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
A massive protest rally organized by the Roman Catholic Church
and former president Corazon Aquino will be held on Sunday to
protest the Charter change moves.
</P>
<P>
"In my view, the businessmen, exporters and importers and even
the banks have fears about the September 21 rally," said the
president of the Bankers Association of the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
