<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
weakened further today after a much-anticipated speech by Reserve
Bank of Australia (RBA) Governor Ian Macfarlane disappointed
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
With no major economic data in recent days to point the way,
Macfarlane's address in Tokyo this afternoon had been considered
by the markets a chance for the RBA to give some indication of the
direction of monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Macfarlane gave a generally positive report card on the
Australian economy, but singled out unemployment as the main
challenge for policy makers.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the RBA planned to cut interest rates further by
the end of the year, Macfarlane said "I am better off not
answering that question," but added that monetary policy remained
an important option to achieve sustained economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the day at 71.64 US cents down
from Wednesday's close of 71.95.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 86.70 from
86.90 against the Japanese yen and was at 1.2675 from 1.2751
against the German mark.  
</P>
