<HEADLINE> Zambia News Agency to Merge with Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
decided to merge the government-owned Zambia News Agency ZANA and
another news service Zambia Information Service ZIS, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia quoted Laura Harrison, permanent secretary of
the information and broadcasting ministry, as saying Wednesday in
Lusaka that the Zambian government would soon merge ZANA and ZIS
in order to rationalize their operations, curb duplication of
services and uphold professionalism among the staff.
</P>
<P>
She added that following the merger, some wings of ZANA and
ZIS would be commercialised to make them viable.
</P>
<P>
In the interview with the newspaper, Harrision also disclosed
a decision made by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to
award Zambia the majority shares of Pan-African News Agency PANA
in the privatisation of the beleaguered service.
</P>
<P>
At an ordinary session held in Cairo, Egypt last June,
information ministers from 41 African countries agreed that
Zambia can take 78 shares of the total 100 shares since it topped
other member countries in clearing their indebtedness to PANA
accrued over the years as demanded by the OAU to qualify for
shares, explained Harrison.
</P>
<P>
However, she couldn't say exactly how the remaining 22 shares
have been distributed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
