<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Vows to Root Out Campus Cultism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to set up a special
tribunal to try all offenses related to cultism and cult-related
activities in the tertiary institutions from the next academic
session.
</P>
<P>
The government determination to root out cultism on the
campuses was disclosed on Wednesday by major-general Bashir
Salihu Magashi, the general officer commanding 2nd mechanized
division.
</P>
<P>
Magashi, who is also member of the supreme Provisional Ruling
Council (PRC), also said that vice-chancellors, rectors, provosts
and students affairs officers of the tertiary institutions would
be empowered to screen students seeking admission into their
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The government decision came at a time of renewed cult
violence at the University of Lagos which claimed the lives of
two students early this month.
</P>
<P>
Institutions of higher learning in Nigeria have become hotbeds
of cult-related violence since early 1990s, and authorities have
tried to curb the trend, but with little or no results.
</P>
<P>
At a one-day workshop for youths, student leaders and
voluntary organizations in Ibadan, western Nigeria, the PRC
member lamented the complete change in the moral values of the
youths.
</P>
<P>
"The menace of social vices has been recognized to be a result
of incessant search for wealth on the part of youths who have
mostly become drug peddlers, hired assassins, prostitutes and
armed robbers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of drug abuse among our youths is a dangerous trend
that must be stopped for it not only destroys the mind but also
the individual," the major-general said.
</P>
<P>
Crimes are committed when the perpetrators have become
emboldened after consumption of hard drugs, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
