<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Agree to Speed up Release of Civilian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- India and Pakistan today
agreed to expedite the release of civilian detainees belonging to
either side but deferred a decision on setting up of a joint
mechanism to tackle contentious issues including Jammu and
Kashmir, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued at the end of the third round of
Indo-Pakistan foreign secretary level talks said that the two
sides decided that the concerned authorities of both countries
would speed up the process of freeing civilian detainees.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the decision to speed up the release of
civilian detainees was taken as a follow up of the meeting between
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
during the SAARC (South Asia Association for Regional Cooperation)
summit in Male, Maldives, in May this year where they had agreed
that the two governments would take measures in this regard.
</P>
<P>
It went on that further consideration was required in
operationalizing the joint mechanism agreed to deal with
contentious issues during the second round of talks in Islamabad
in June.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the foreign secretaries decided to
adjourn now and reconvene their meeting at a mutually convenient
date.
</P>
<P>
The three-day talks, which began here on Tuesday between Indian
Foreign Secretary K. Raghunath and his Pakistan counterpart
Shamshad Ahmad, focused on discussions of a joint statement issued
on June 23 at the end of the second round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Both sides had different interpretations of the June 23
statement, especially paragraphs relating to the setting up of a
joint mechanism to tackle all outstanding issues between the two
countries including the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
While Pakistan maintains that both sides have agreed in the
statement to set up a joint working group on Jammu and Kashmir,
India firmly denies such an interpretation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
