<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Growth to Be Lower This Year: Singapore PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong said that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) will see its average growth rate lowered by one to two
percent this year after the recent financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said today that Goh made the
comment to the media following his address to the US-ASEAN
Business Council in Chicago on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the impact the recent turmoil has on the Singapore
economy and its growth, Goh said that he thought it would affect
Singapore by one to 1.5 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
"The Singapore economy depends also on the performance of the
regional economies. We buy, we sell, we invest in these countries.
When their growth is affected, ours will also be affected," Goh
said.
</P>
<P>
"I would reckon that on the whole, if we take an average, ASEAN
will shave its growth rate by maybe one to two percent. Some
countries will lose more, some countries will do better. But on
the average, maybe we should all scale down by one to two
percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, in response to press queries, the Press Secretary to
Prime Minister Goh said today in a statement that the recent
currency crisis in the region "would not have an immediate effect
on Singapore's economic growth."
</P>
<P>
"The economy is still forecast to grow between six and seven
percent this year especially with the strong pickup of the
manufacturing sector," the Press Secretary said, adding, "however,
if the regional economies slow down in the next few years, there
would be an impact on our economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Goh is in Chicago on a four-day visit to the
United States after his visit to Mexico last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
