<P>
Flemming Larsen, deputy director of the IMF's Research
Department, told Xinhua: "If the current growth trend of nine
percent is maintained (in China), in about a decade the weight of
the Chinese economy, with Hong Kong excluded, will be similar to
the weight of the United States' or the weight of the European
Union's."
</P>
<P>
China's real GDP grew on average by over nine percent a year
between 1978 and 1996, and the IMF predicts in its latest report
"World Economic Outlook" that the growth momentum will continue in
1997 at 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
With its tremendous economic growth, China is playing an
increasingly important role in the IMF. "China's position in the
IMF is growing, and it also plays a constructive role in regional
affairs," Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
China recently supported the IMF efforts to bail out the Thai
economy by contributing one billion U.S. dollars to a rescue
package worth 17.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Larsen noted that the impressive economic growth in China has
been coupled with significant structural transformation, and
gradual opening and integration of the economy with the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
But China's transition to a market-based economy is still an
unfinished agenda, according to the IMF official, who listed four
main challenges the country has to face -- financial sector
reform, state enterprise reform, fiscal reform and regional
disparities.
</P>
<P>
He said he was impressed that at the 15th National Party
Congress, the Chinese leaders have shown their political will and
determination to reform state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Monetary Expert Diagnoses Currency Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The peso devaluation that hit
the Philippines since July 11 was inevitable owing to the
government's opening up of its economy to foreign investments, a
local monetary expert said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson
during a roundtable discussion, Diwa Gunigundo, director of the
Department of Economic Research, said that the country's adoption
of a liberalized economy made it vulnerable to pressures from the
onslaught of market forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines found it difficult to go against the currency
woes because billions of U.S. dollars are involved in this crisis,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot do this at this time because we only have 11.5
billion U.S. dollars in international reserves," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said it is difficult to have a stable exchange rate system
under an open economy such as that of the Philippines, noting that
most of the country's manufacturing sector use foreign exchange
for imported orders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he attributed the currency turbulence in the region
to the manipulation of foreign fund managers who help lump the
region's economies into one basket.
</P>
<P>
This is coupled by the fact that the U.S. economy continues to
grow this year, attracting foreign investors to pull their funds
out of Southeast Asia and put them in the United States, Gunigundo
said.
</P>
<P>
Since early July, the Thai baht, the Malaysian ringgit, the
Indonesian rupiah, the Singaporean dollar and the Philippine peso
all tumbled sharply amid the current financial turmoil sweeping
the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
