<HEADLINE> Performance of IMF, World Bank Adequate: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Asia's
business leaders have described the performance of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank as "adequate"
in Asia, said the latest Asian Executives Poll, carried out
jointly by the region's two major business medium.
</P>
<P>
Across the region, 51 percent of respondents, which include
chairmen, managing directors and other top corporate executives in
10 Asian economies, assess the performance of the IMF as
"adequate" and 57 percent rate the World Bank's performance
similarly.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Executives Poll, a weekly fax poll conducted by the
Far Eastern Economic Review and Asia Business News, said that 54
percent of business leaders say the IMF's role is "important", and
41 percent say "very important".
</P>
<P>
The poll also said that 55 percent of business leaders polled
say that the World Bank plays an "important" role in helping
Southeast Asian economies, which have just experienced a financial
crisis. Over 30 percent say the World Bank's role is "very
important".
</P>
<P>
The Far Eastern Economic Review is Asia's first regional
publication and recently celebrated half a century of publishing.
</P>
<P>
Asia Business News is the region's first television service
dedicated to business news and financial analysis produced in Asia
with an Asian perspective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
