<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Foreign Reserve Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September (Xinhua) -- Lebanese foreign exchange
reserve has registered a fall this month for the first time in the
past 17 months, the Beirut Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Bank of Lebanon was quoted as saying that
the foreign reserve dropped by 160.4 million U.S. dollars to 6.437
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the fall is expected in view of the due
repayment of treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
But he maintained the situation will be stablized as domestic
demands on the dollar have been decreasing in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Lebanon has pledged to intervene in the
by keeping a narrow bid-offer spread and ensuring a steady
appreciation of the Lebanese pound.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the central bank lowered its bid-offer intervention
band for the local currency to 1,529.50-1,539.50 pounds to the
dollar from 1,530-1,540 a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's fiscal policy, based on high domestic borrowing and
interest rates, has led to the inflow of large amount of capital
and gradual appreciation of the Lebanese pound in the recent
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
