<HEADLINE> Taiwan Criminal Suspect Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross organization of
the Chinese mainland handed over a suspect in a financial crime to
its counterpart in Taiwan here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The repatriated man, Cai Zhiwei, a 27-year-old Taiwan bank
clerk, fled to Hong Kong on April 30, this year with part of the
31.44 million Taiwan yuan he had stolen from customer accounts at
bank.
</P>
<P>
Cai entered Shenzhen on May 1, carrying one million Hong Kong
dollars and 100,000 US dollars in cash, and traveler's checks
worth 450,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
He was held for questioning when he cashed the traveler's
checks at the Bank of China Shenzhen Branch on May 5. The funds he
deposited in a local bank were also frozen.
</P>
<P>
Among the items that were handed over today included 227,000 US
dollars in cash, Cai's identification papers, his travel
documents, bank savings account book and several forged seals.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan Red Cross representative expressed his thanks for
the cooperation from its mainland counterpart and hoped that the
involvement in cooperation would continue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides worked out a repatriation agreement in September
1990 and since have completed a total of 14 repatriations of
illegal immigrants and crime suspects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
