<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internal Israeli Deal Postpones High Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- An unexpected agreement
between Israeli government and the settlers today led the High
Court to delay its ruling on the heated housing dispute in East
Jerusalem's Ras Amud Arab neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the three settler families, who moved into
two houses in Ras Amud Sunday night and sparked a new crisis
in the Israeli-Palestinian ties, had reached a compromise with
the government that they would leave the houses in exchange for
the government's approval to allow religious Jews to hold
seminars there.
</P>
<P>
The settlers made the concession because they insisted that
the religious Jews would continue the Jewish presence in Ras
Amud to underline the Israeli sovereignty claim over East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected agreement came just ahead of the pending
ruling by the high court on a petition filed by the Miami-based
billionare Irving Moscowitz, who purchased the houses and plans
to build a Jewish settlement there, against the government's
planned actions to evict the settlers.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid an escalation of the tense situation which
feuls fear about an eruption of Palestinian violence, Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has indicated that he would
use force to evict the settlers from Ras Amud.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the court would support the
government's actions, citing the reasons for state security and
public order.
</P>
<P>
The settlers' presence in Ras Amud has triggered angry
protests from the Palestinians, who warned about an outbreak of
violence that threatens to kill the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian peace activists have been holding
demonstrations for the past days in Ras Amud, demanding for the
immediate evacuation of the settlers and resumption of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over Ras Amud reflects the sensitivity of the
dispute over the status of Jerusalem, which is set to be settled
through the final-status talks between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israel has claimed the whole Jerusalem, including the Arab
East Jerusalem it took over in the 1967 war, as its eternal and
indivisible capital, while the PNA hopes to establish a state
with East Jerusalem as capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelter Forest Project Surrounding Beijing Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Some Beijing residents have
found that the capital's climate has become gentler, with less
dust and grit in the air.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the improvement to a greening project in the
capital's neighbor, Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.47 million hectares of ecological shelter forest has
been established there, which has "in effect improved the ecology
in Beijing and Tianjin," said an official in charge of the
project, adding that more than 700,000 local residents have shaken
off poverty by working for the planting program.
</P>
<P>
The project, started in 1986, covers six cities and 50 counties
surrounding Beijing and Tianjin, including Zhangjiakou, Chengde
and Qinhuangdao.
</P>
<P>
Before the project began, Beijing was beseiged by heavy dust
storms for about 20 days a year. That number has decreased to
around 11, officials say, and less silt has entered the Panjiakou
and Miyun reservoirs, which are Beijing and Tianjin's water source.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the forest by-product processing industry in the
area covered by the project has generated more than one billion
yuan (about 125 million US dollars) in profit in the past decade,
benefiting over a million farmers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Holocaust Memorial Museum to Go High-tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Holocaust
Memorial Museum (Yad Vashem) will undergo high-tech renovations
in order to accommodate a growing stream of visitors, especially
the young people.
</P>
<P>
The renovations, named "Yad Vashem 2001" project, will be
conducted according to a new design by the prize-winning
architect Moshe Safdie, who plans a dramatic wedge that will cut
sharply across the Mountain of Herzl, and features a huge
underground exhibition center, computer stations and video
theaters.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated to cost 50 million U.S. dollars, a
third of which will be paid by the American Society for Yad
Vashem.
</P>
<P>
Avner Shalev, Yad Vashem's Director, said the project targets
a young generation growing up in the computer age and "in a
period in which there will be fewer living Holocaust survivors"
to tell their story.
</P>
<P>
He noted a tremendous increase in interest in Holocaust
studies, and the museum's increasing popularity, with nearly 1.4
million people having visited in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Explaining his design at a news conference Wednesday, Safdie
said he had sought a "non-building" kind of structure, believing
that "conventional buildings are not appropriate for telling the
story of the Holocaust."
</P>
<P>
The design features a new entrance plaza that seeks to avoid
the appearance of a train station, and which should "separate
the sacred from the profane."
</P>
<P>
In the visitors' center, 12 hollow columns will support a
trellis-like roof over a 2,500 meter structure. Displays will
tell an introductory story to Yad Vashem.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will cross a bridge on the Avenue of the Righteous
Among the Nations before entering the actual museum, which will
be shaped like a 175-meter long spine. Much of it will be
underground, providing an expanded 3,000 square meters of
exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
Once through this tunnel-like museum, visitors may choose
between an art gallery, a hall housing temporary exhibits, or
proceed to the hall of Remembrance of Children's Memorial.
</P>
<P>
Computer stations will offer multimedia presentations. A
screening center will show documentaries or other films on
request, and offer master copies of videos of tens of thousands
of survivors made by the famous American film director Steven
Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
Safdie said that the new museum will be one-way and
completely linear "like the story itself - it will start
somewhere and end somewhere."
</P>
<P>
He added that his design would enable the museum to remain
open during pending renovations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks Tumble Amid Currency Woes, Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market
took a beating today as the benchmark composite index tumbled for
the seventh straight day amid currency woes and political
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
The composite index fell by 64.11 points, or 3.09 percent to
close at 2,009.85 points while the broader all share index slipped
by 20.53 points, or 3.13 percent to end at 645.30 points.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.6 billion shares worth 62 million U.S. dollars were
traded in today's trading.
</P>
<P>
Dealers and brokers attributed the bearish performance of the
stock market to a number of factors including the currency woes
sweeping the region, political unstability arising from Charter
change moves and a loan default by a local consumer electronics
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
The peso dropped to a new low of 34.05 to one U.S. dollar today
due to the fall of currencies in neighboring countries and the
economic and political difficulties in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Some one million people would hold a mass rally in Metro Manila
on Sunday to voice their anger over Charter change moves seeking
to lift the term limit of President Fidel Ramos, sending foreign
portfolio investors to withdraw their funds out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EYCO Group, which manufactures small home
appliances under the brand name of Nikon, admitted that it is
having difficulties in paying its loans to banks, creating a
sentiment of selling off.
</P>
<P>
Suffering most from today's sell-off are the banking and
property stocks. The Philippine National Bank share prices
nose-dived by 16.67 percent to its six-year low while the property
stocks, compounded by the impending supply glut and higher
borrowing cost, continued to be in the doldrums.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
