<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The Socialist government of France has presented a project to
reduce family allowances for families earning more than 25,000
francs (4,200 U.S. dollars) per month, which will cut such social
benefits in about 9 percent of the families receiving them now.
</P>
<P>
-- The agreement concluded in Houston Tuesday evening between
Morocco and the Polisario Front to hold a referendum in the former
Spanish colony disputed by Rabat and the Saharoui independence
movement for 22 years are equivalent to the Oslo agreement and
Dayton agreement in terms of both significance and difficulty for
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In its 1998 draft budget law, the Socialist government will
raise the rate of General Social Security Contribution tax (CSG)
from people with high incomes and savings, which will allow them to
increase state revenue by 18 to 20 billion francs (3 to 3.3 billion
US dollars). Meanwhile, the government will cut by 6 billion francs
(1 billion US dollars) spending in family aid.
</P>
<P>
-- The French football team Paris Saint-Germain scored a good
start in the League of Champions of Europe on Wednesday by beating
the Swedish IFK Goteborg 3-0. Manchester, Dynamo of Kiev, Real
Madrid, Juventus of Turin, Borussia of Dortmund, Newcastle, Sporting
of Portugal and Bayen of Munich also won in other matches of the
professional league. 
