<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Ends Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga left here this afternoon for home after
concluding a four-day official visit to Malaysia, which she
described as "very successful".
</P>
<P>
She told a news conference prior to her departure that the
visit came out with "practical results" in the form of several
investment agreements signed between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreements included one on avoiding double taxation and tax
evasion and one on economic, scientific and technical cooperation
on governmental basis.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian private sector companies also signed four memorandums
of understanding with the Board of investment of Sri Lanka on
project proposals concerning the development of two industrial
townships, the setting up of an air cargo hub terminal at the
Colombo International airport and an exhibition and convention
center in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"Most important of all is that we were able to establish very
close contacts with the Malaysian government... and I think we can
develop this relationship on all foundations we have built," she
said.
</P>
<P>
During her visit, Kumaratunga held talks with Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad on expanding bilateral cooperation in
the fields of economy, investment, training and information
technology, and on several international issues.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said that during the visit they have learned a lot
from Malaysia's experience. Sri Lanka was interested in sending
its officers to receive training or study in Malaysia, which had
successfully reformed its Civil Service, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
