<HEADLINE> Mass Resignations Hit Tehran Municipality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Twelve mayors governing 17
districts of Iran's capital Tehran submitted resignations to
Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi Wednesday, the English daily
Iran News reported today.
</P>
<P>
They cited lack of appropriate conditions for continuance of
their services as the reason for their resignation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi, however, rejected the resignations and asked them to
"strenuously continue their services."
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be a strong protest against the recent move
of arrests of municipal officials of Tehran on charges of alleged
financial corruption.
</P>
<P>
Seven high-ranking officials of Tehran municipality, including
Karbaschi's financial and administrative director, his security
chief and a mayor of district, were arrested in July after Iran's
Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei launched the nationwide
anti-corruption move in June.
</P>
<P>
On July 31, more than 100 leftist and liberal parliamentary
deputies published a letter, condemning the arrests of the
officials.
</P>
<P>
The Judiciary said in a statement on August 14 that the
investigations of the cases of alleged corruption fall within the
authority of Tehran Justice Department and is closely supervised
by the head of the Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The Judiciary said it is independent, fair and politics-free in
dealing with cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
