<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roth: Strategic Dialogue With China to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official
said here today that the U.S. administration would continue its
strategic dialogue with China to expand cooperation and narrow
differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Attending a Senate hearing on "1997 China policy Act", a bill
presented by nine senators last week, Stanley Roth, Assistant
Secretary for the Bureau of East Asia and Pacific Affairs, said
that it was consistent with the policy pursued in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
"For the past 25 years, six presidents have sought a proper
balance in our relationship with China, promoting our interest,
cooperating where possible in areas of common concern, but also,
frankly, confronting differences and trying to narrow them," said
Roth, who visited China recently in preparation for a state visit
to the U.S. by Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
"The Clinton administration's strategy of comprehensive
engagement toward China is based on the premise that it is
profoundly in our interest to work toward the emergence of China
as a great power that is stable, open and non-aggressive," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The bill complains about the lack of "progress" in China's
human rights, nuclear proliferation and religion issues, and
threatens to impose unilateral sanctions on China.
</P>
<P>
Roth spoke firmly against still treating China as an enemy,
noting profound changes have already taken place in the world's
most populous country, which is growing as one of the biggest
economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
"To treat China as an enemy risks becoming a self-fulfilling
prophecy, and that serves no one's interest, least of all the
United States," he told the law-makers.
</P>
<P>
Roth believed that unilateral sanctions and other unilateral
steps would be "counterproductive" and particularly "ill-timed as
we move toward the first of our two state visits with the People's
Republic of China."
</P>
<P>
President Jiang and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton agreed
last year in Manila to meet this fall in Washington and next
spring in Beijing. Preparations for Jiang's trip are in full
swing, according to officials from both sides.
</P>
<P>
"President Jiang Zemin's visit to Washington and President
Clinton's return visit to China next year provide the opportunity
to make concrete progress on issues of mutual concern," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that mandate sanctions would "cut us off from our
current productive dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Other senators present at the hearing also expressed concern
that such an anti-China bill, if adopted, would hold back the
progress in the Sino-American relationship and worsen the prospect
for cooperation between the two big nations.
</P>
<P>
The bill seems to be far away from becoming a law since strong
objections voiced by the administration officials and some
senators as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Congress in Ordinary People's Eyes (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Wang Erjiang, a model worker
who has won a "May 1" Labor Medal granted to excellent workers
nationwide, has asked journalists to help him collect newspapers
published during the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party
of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
"I want all newspapers covering the Congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang works at the Anshan Iron and Steel Company, one of China's
largest steel producers, located in northeast China's Liaoning
province. He explained to his colleagues at work the report
delivered by Jiang Zemin at the opening session of the congress.
</P>
<P>
The idea of collecting newspapers came to him when some of the
workers complained that they could not find newspapers in the
workshops.
</P>
<P>
Wang decided to gather newspapers for fellow workers so that
plenty of information about the congress would be available for
all. He plans to save the newspapers once all the workers have
finished reading.
</P>
<P>
So far he has copies of 46 different newspapers, including
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph," "People's Daily," "Anshan Daily" and a
daily newspaper published by and issued within Anshan.
</P>
<P>
"State-owned enterprises will surely overcome the difficulties
they face," Wang said, full of confidence in Jiang's report. He
added that the report points out both the means and direction for
the development of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Liu Meixun was ready to rewrite a just-finished book,
"Following the Road of Socialism with Chinese Characteristics."
</P>
<P>
"The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) is a new milestone," said Liu, director of the economic
research institute of Qinghua University. "We must add new
contents that were unveiled as breakthroughs in Jiang Zemin's
report."
</P>
<P>
Liu and several colleagues finished the 300,000-word book
before the congress opened. After a week of close watch on the
meeting, Liu decided to revise her book.
</P>
<P>
"Jiang's report has answered many problems that puzzled
theorists," she said, adding that the report would emancipate
people's minds.
</P>
<P>
Liu planned to ask co-authors to also revise their
contributions to the book after they study Jiang's report. She
said that their focus would be on chapters on reform of
state-owned enterprises and on holding high the banner of Deng
Xiaoping Theory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
