<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are the major news
items in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
New Nigerian
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria and Chad signed a communique Wednesday, agreeing to
actualize the construction of direct highway and power links
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Nigerians living in Equatorial Guinea have cried out for
help over the continued and persistent torture, detention and
beatings by the country's policemen.
</P>
<P>
Daily Times
</P>
<P>
-- At least 2.3 million Nigerians out of the estimated 10
million population have been tested positive to HIV (human immune
deficiency virus).
</P>
<P>
The Guardian
</P>
<P>
-- Sierra Leone's military government claimed Wednesday to
have mobilized 16,000 armed men to defend Freetown against the
West African Peacekeeping Force but the Nigerian defense
headquarters alleged the junta had launched a genocide against
the Nigerian-Hausa community in the country.
</P>
<P>
This Day
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund has described Nigeria's
economic performance this year as disappointing as it puts the
nation's 1997 economic growth rate at 3.6 percent, 1.9 percent
off the 5.5 percent target of the Nigerian government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
