<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Deny Opening Skies to Singapore at Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will
definitely deny Singapore's demand for "open sky" air service
rights when the negotiating panels of the two countries meet on
September 23-24 in Singapore, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Franklin Ebdalin, who chairs the Philippine panel to the air
talks, was quoted as saying that the panel has already taken this
position even before they meet their Singaporean counterparts.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore has requested for the air service accord
talks to justify its demand for open skies with the Philippines.
Under such an accord, designated air carriers will have unlimited
flight access and rights to and from any point of either country.
</P>
<P>
It will be grossly disadvantageous for the Philippines to grant
the request since the arrangement will be heavily in Singapore's
favor, he said, adding Singapore has only a piece of sky while the
Philippines has the entire space above its archipelago for
Singapore planes.
</P>
<P>
Ebdalin, however, disclosed that the Philippine panel may agree
to recommend the grant of additional rights for Singapore's air
carriers to fly to any Philippine international airport except
Manila.
</P>
<P>
He said that additional flights outside Manila may actually
help accelerate the development of the country's outlying regions
into major international air routes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
