<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Army Sets Up Unit to Probe Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Army has
established a special unit to investigate public complaints
against army personnel, the national news agency Lankapuvath said
today.
</P>
<P>
Army Commander Lieutenant General Rohan Daluwatta told the
agency that the unit was set up to probe public complaints of
bribery, corruption, human rights violations and other offenses in
the army.
</P>
<P>
It would also serve as a deterrent against indiscipline and
wrongdoing, the commander added.
</P>
<P>
He said all those found guilty will be dealt with firmly and
swiftly and will receive maximum punishment.
</P>
<P>
He has asked the provost marshal of the army to lead the
special unit and report to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
