<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli security forces detained five Palestinians
overnight in a stone-throwing clash in the West Bank city of
Hebron, Israel Radio reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The clash began when Palestinians refused to show their
identity cards to Israeli soldiers guarding the Jewish Quarter,
where there are still some 450 Jewish settlers after Israeli troop
redeployment from 80 percent of the city early this year.
(Israel-Palestine-Hebron Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia has curbed its economic slump with a moderate
gain in industrial manufacturing and a drop in minimum living
expenses, according to a report issued Wednesday by the National
Statistic Committee of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) from January to August
maintained the same level as last year, ending the plunge that
started in the early 1990s. Industrial production is up 1.4
percent compared with the same period last year and witnessed a
three percent hike in August, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
(Russia-Economy-Recovery)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said
Wednesday that the treaty signed between Russia and Armenia late
last month is not directed against Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual Assistance,
signed by Russian and Armenian presidents on August 29 in Moscow,
aimed to strengthen the two countries' traditional good relations
and all-round cooperation in political, economic, military,
scientific, cultural and other areas. Russia is upset over the
fact that some people in Nagorno-Karabakh want to resort to force
to solve the nine-year conflict between Armenia and Azerbaijan
over the disputed enclave, Primakov said in a statement carried by
local media. (Russia-Armenia-Azerbaijan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- The Czech Republic and Germany Wednesday finished a
three-day joint military exercise in the western part of the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
The Czech News Agency reported that some 1,400 military
personnel from the two countries joined in the exercise,
code-named "Common Goal 97," which is intended to train and
condition the countries' two air forces to coordinate and simulate
aerial combat. The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) also
sent observers. (Czech-Germany-Exercise) 
</P>
</TEXT>
