<HEADLINE> S. African Gold Industry Signs Wage Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's National
Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and the Chamber of Mines have signed a
two-year agreement linking improvement in wages to productivity,
local daily, Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
A target of producing more to help rescue the slump gold
industry was agreed upon in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the agreement, about 100,000 mine workers were facing
retrenchment following gold price crash to below 320 U.S. Dollars
an ounce in global market in early July.
</P>
<P>
Last year gold production in South Africa registered only
494.6 tons, the lowest since 1956. The highest was more than
1,000 tons recorded in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest agreement officially signed Wednesday, the
minimum wage for lower surface and underground workers has been
raised from 1,000 Rand (213 U.S. Dollars) to 1150 Rand (244 U.S.
Dollars) a month, representing an increment of 20 percent for
some mines.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the workers will receive increase of between nine
and 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
NUM's General Secretary Kgalema Motlanthe described the deal
as significant and remarkable. "It is a historic agreement for us
to have achieved these increases. It's a hell of an achievement."
</P>
<P>
Frans Barker, the chamber's deputy industrial relations
advisor, said the agreement had the potential of changing the
country's industrial relations landscape.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
