<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, Tanzania Urged to Integrate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian senior official
has urged Zambia and Tanzania to integrate socially and
economically, an English-language newspaper Zambia Daily Mail
reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Zambian Foreign Affairs Minister Lawrence
Shimba Wednesday in the capital, Tanzanian Home Affairs Minister
Ameir Mohammed observed that the two countries have vast economic
potentials which need to be explored and improved upon, saying
they should adopt a "positive" and "vigorous approach towards
economic and social integration.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed cited the need to explore the transport sector, the
tourism industry and the mining areas if the two neighbors are to
integrate in wide dimensions.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that plans were underway to turn the once slave
trade route on Lake Tanganyika on borders of the two countries
for tourism purposes and also for opening up the Tazara
(Tanzania-Zambia) Railway Corridor into a manufacturing giant.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed challenged the Tanzanian Chambers of Commerce and the
Zambian counterparts to come up with solutions and tasks that
would realize the promotion of tourism and other aspects of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two countries should not just concentrate
on bilateral cooperation in the economic sectors at the expense
of social and cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed, together with two deputy ministers from Tanzania's
finance and communication and transport ministries respectively,
arrived in Lusaka Wednesday to join their Zambian colleagues
attending the sixth joint permanent commission, which was
established in 1989 and aims to promote economic and social
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with the Zambian Foreign Minister, Mohammed
also emphasized the need for the two countries to strengthen and
revamp the operations of the joint commission which he said has
not performed as expected.
</P>
<P>
"The commission must explore new areas of cooperation and
soldier on in our goals to attain strong economies and political
endeavors for our two countries, said the Tanzanian official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Holocaust Memorial Museum to Go High-tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Holocaust
Memorial Museum (Yad Vashem) will undergo high-tech renovations
in order to accommodate a growing stream of visitors, especially
the young people.
</P>
<P>
The renovations, named "Yad Vashem 2001" project, will be
conducted according to a new design by the prize-winning
architect Moshe Safdie, who plans a dramatic wedge that will cut
sharply across the Mountain of Herzl, and features a huge
underground exhibition center, computer stations and video
theaters.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated to cost 50 million U.S. dollars, a
third of which will be paid by the American Society for Yad
Vashem.
</P>
<P>
Avner Shalev, Yad Vashem's Director, said the project targets
a young generation growing up in the computer age and "in a
period in which there will be fewer living Holocaust survivors"
to tell their story.
</P>
<P>
He noted a tremendous increase in interest in Holocaust
studies, and the museum's increasing popularity, with nearly 1.4
million people having visited in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Explaining his design at a news conference Wednesday, Safdie
said he had sought a "non-building" kind of structure, believing
that "conventional buildings are not appropriate for telling the
story of the Holocaust."
</P>
<P>
The design features a new entrance plaza that seeks to avoid
the appearance of a train station, and which should "separate
the sacred from the profane."
</P>
<P>
In the visitors' center, 12 hollow columns will support a
trellis-like roof over a 2,500 meter structure. Displays will
tell an introductory story to Yad Vashem.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will cross a bridge on the Avenue of the Righteous
Among the Nations before entering the actual museum, which will
be shaped like a 175-meter long spine. Much of it will be
underground, providing an expanded 3,000 square meters of
exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
Once through this tunnel-like museum, visitors may choose
between an art gallery, a hall housing temporary exhibits, or
proceed to the hall of Remembrance of Children's Memorial.
</P>
<P>
Computer stations will offer multimedia presentations. A
screening center will show documentaries or other films on
request, and offer master copies of videos of tens of thousands
of survivors made by the famous American film director Steven
Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
Safdie said that the new museum will be one-way and
completely linear "like the story itself - it will start
somewhere and end somewhere."
</P>
<P>
He added that his design would enable the museum to remain
open during pending renovations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dogs to Sniff Bombs Before Mass Rally in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Police will use six dogs
trained to sniff bombs to check an area in the Philippine capital
of Manila where a mass rally would be held on Sunday, the
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Jose Capacete, superintendent of the Western Police Bomb
Disposal Unit, was quoted as saying that the dogs are part of a
team who would assure that no bombs or explosives are planted in
the area.
</P>
<P>
About 200 traffic policemen will also be deployed throughout
the city to make certain the smooth flow of traffic during the
rally, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rally was called by former President Corazon Aquino and
Cardinal Jaime Sin to mount pressure on President Fidel Ramos
against any drive to seek for re-election or an extension of his
term through revising the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The president has revealed to the public that he may stay in
power after his term ends in June next year.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people who oppose the extension of Ramos' term
through charter change moves would attend the rally. Ramos had met
with Aquino and Sin but failed to persuade them to cancel the
rally.
</P>
<P>
Since early this month, a spate of bomb threats has haunted
Metro Manila after two explosions killed six people and wounded 60
others. It was reported that the planned rally would also be
bombed.
</P>
<P>
The opposition said the threats were made by Ramos' supporters
who wish to give the president a chance to declare martial law by
sending the country into chaos.
</P>
<P>
Political uncertainty arising from charter change moves is
scaring foreign investors to pull out their funds out of the
country, fueling the meltdown of the peso in the current financial
turmoil sweeping the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
