<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Politicians Condemn Ras Al-Amud Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli politicians have
condemned the movement of Jews into Ras Al-Amud and asked the
expulsion of U.S. businessman Irving Moskowitz who bankrolled the
Jewish movement, the Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Shas Party leaders joined the opposition in condemning the
Jewish movement, calling it a "provocation of gentiles" that
could lead to attacks.
</P>
<P>
The party's spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia issued a statement
Wednesday, saying the Ras Al-Amud action "could incite an already
volatile situation in Jerusalem and was totally unnecessary."
</P>
<P>
MP Nissim Zvilli of Labor party called last night the
expulsion of Moskowitz, alleging that his activities of
bankrolling the movement of settlers into the Arab neighborhood
endangered public safety and state security.
</P>
<P>
"Moskowitz's irresponsible initiative is damaging security and
may lead Israel to a blood bath," he said, adding that "such a man
must not be allow to remain in Israel."
</P>
<P>
Three Jewish families moved into Ras Al-Amud on Sunday night
and their action has caused a tense situation in East
Jerusalem. Moskowitz is behind their movement, saying he bought
the property in Ras Al-Amud and the Israeli government has no
right to force the Jewish settlers to move out from Ras Al-Amud.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli High Court stated this morning to hear a
petition by Moskowitz, who is demanding a temporary injunction
to prevent any attempt by the Israeli government to evict
the Jewish settlers from Ras Al-Amud.
</P>
<P>
Meretz Party leader Yossi Sarid, however, asked last night to
bar Moskowitz from leaving Israel. He should "stay here and eat
the broth he has spoiled for us. He must not be allowed
to escape when the fire spreads and starts burning everything,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Several Labor Party MPs also demanded an urgent meeting of
parliament's State Control Committee to examine how decision was
made to allow Jews into Ras Al-Amud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
