<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Awarded by Hong Kong Foundation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Two scientific research
teams and 20 young scientists have received cash awards from the
Qiu Shi Science and Technologies Foundation of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng, Chairman of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress Qiao Shi, and Vice-premier Li
Lanqing sent letters of congratulations to the winners and the
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Chen Ning Yang, Prof. Y. W. Kan and some 400 noted
Chinese scientists from both at home and overseas attended on
Wednesday the awards ceremony held in east China's Zhejiang
University, where the Qiu Shi Science and Technologies Foundation
was established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A team of nine scientists led by Wang Qiu and Xing Qiyi won a
group honor for outstanding achievements in producing synthetic
insulin. The team was given 1.5 million yuan (181,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Another team of eight scientists, led by Zhu Maoyan and Li
Guoxiang, won the prize for achieving outstanding results from
research on the early stage of the evolution of life, and the
eruption in the Cambrian Period, a period that began 570 million
years ago and spanned over next 70 million years, in which rocks
of the Cambrian system were deposited. The group received one
million yuan (120,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty scientists including Wen Lan, Wang Wei, Wu Qi, and Wang
Zhixin each got 40,000 US dollars for taking the honors as
outstanding young scientists.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994 through a grant of 20 million US dollars
donated by Hong Kong entrepreneur Cha Chi Ming, the Qiu Shi
Science and Technologies Foundation is aimed to promote China's
science and research professions.
</P>
<P>
Among the judges of the awards are Prof. Shiing-shen Chern, a
Chinese-American mathematician and foreign academician of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS); Prof. Chen Ning Yang, a
physicist and Nobel Prize winner; Prof. Zhou Guangzhao, a famous
physicist and former CAS president; Nobel Prize winner and Chemist
Prof. Yuan Tseh Lee; and Prof. Y.W. Kan, a noted professor of
medical science.
</P>
<P>
The foundation has presented awards to more than 100 Chinese
scientists who have made great contributions in the research of
mathematics, physics, chemistry and medical science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
