<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Pacific Forum Meeting Opens in Cook Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAROTONGAN (Cook Islands), September 17 (Xinhua) -- The 28th
South Pacific Forum opened here today to discuss a number of
issues facing the region.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister of the Cook Islands Sir Geoffrey Henry, the
current chairman of the forum, opened the meeting which brought
together the presidents and prime ministers of the 16 forum member
countries.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Sir Geoffrey said "Over the years since
its founding, the forum has witnessed phenomenal changes in our
region. Perhaps foremost amongst these has been our growing
inter-dependence with the broader international community and the
globalization of the world economy."
</P>
<P>
"During the same period, the end of the cold war and other
developments have brought wholly different perceptions towards
international aid. Inevitably, the emphasis has shifted to the
converse of aid dependency, namely self-reliance and
sustainability."
</P>
<P>
On the models for economic development, he said, "We seek to
utilize what is offered, but not to imitate. We prefer to maintain
our cultural integrity to proceed in our own way."
</P>
<P>
Good intentions need day to day action, leader to leader
interaction, nation to nation cohesion, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed thanks to the governments of Australia, China, New
Zealand and France for their assistance in helping the Cook
Islands to host this forum.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, the leaders will appoint a new
secretary general for the forum, and deliberate on such issues as
regional trade, security, fisheries, climate change and nuclear
shipment.
</P>
<P>
They will also hold bilateral and multilateral talks with the
forum's "dialogue partners", including Britain, China and the
European Union, France, Japan, South Korea and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The South Pacific Forum was initiated in 1971 in Wellington,
New Zealand. Government heads from the forum's member countries
meet annually to discuss a wide range of common issues and
problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
