<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Against Water Hyacinth Approved in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda National
Environment Management Authority (NEMA) has approved integrated
control program against the water hyacinth, reported the local
daily The Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
NEMA executive director John Okedi was quoted as announcing
here on Wednesday that the use of an integrated control program
involving physical (manual and mechanical) and biological control
options are approved and should proceed for immediate
implementation as they have no significant environmental impacts
which either affect the health of the people or the ecological
functioning of Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
He said that the biological option should be implemented as a
long term control strategy.
</P>
<P>
Okedi's recommendation comes at a time when most of the Lake
Victoria landing sites have been choked by the water hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
"When implementing the component involving physical removal,
appropriate disposal sites should be identified for the harvested
weed to avoid reinfestation due to seed dispersal and further
pollution of the lake," Okedi said.
</P>
<P>
NEMA also recommended immediate action, stepping up the use of
physical control, especially at major transportation terminals
and power generation sites.
</P>
<P>
According to NEMA, a boom should be installed at River Kagera
supported by mechanical removal operations. More booms should
also be installed along the river before it enters Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
However, he said use of chemicals, applying herbicides has
never been approved.
</P>
<P>
Okedi said that chemical use was abandoned because of the
legal actions that could be taken upon anybody who applied
chemicals under the constitution and other laws.
</P>
<P>
He said use of herbicides would necessitate multiple
application to control the weed at manageable levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Identify Capital of Yuan Dynasty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists
and historians have recently identified a capital of the Yuan
Dynasty (1271-1368) in the northern province of Hebei.
</P>
<P>
The Yuan Dynasty was estalished by Genghis Khan's grandson
following the defeat of the Song Dynasty. To ensure tight control
over the big empire whose territory spread as far as to Europe,
three capitals were set up by different emperors.
</P>
<P>
The newly-identified capital is located in Zhangbei County of
Hebei. It was in the middle of a route connecting Dadu, or the
greater capital in the present-day Beijing, and Shangdu, or the
upper capital, in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, the other
two capitals of the Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have been excavating at the site for years, but
the status of the city remained unknown for a long period. After
extensive studies of unearthed relics and historical documents,
experts concluded last month that the site was "Zhongdu," or
"middle capital," which was built in the early 14th century.
</P>
<P>
The city greatly benefited from cultural and economic exchanges
between the Mongolians and the Chinese people living in the
hinterland.
</P>
<P>
Protection work is underway to preserve the historical site,
archeologists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
