<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Appeals Food Donation for Drought-Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program
(WFP) has appealed to donors to provide food for some three
million Tanzanians who face severe food shortages over the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by WFP in Nairobi, Kenya, Wednesday said
one million of these will need immediate help to get through the
next three months, according to the local press.
</P>
<P>
"The WFP is preparing an emergency food aid operation in
response to the drought, and appeals to donor countries to make
immediate contributions to ensure that relief food can begin to
quickly reach those most in need," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added, "Food donations typically take a minimum of three to
four months to arrive in Tanzania. However, it is crucial that
relief food distributions get under way as early as September
when food stocks are expected to be exhausted."
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that assessments of Tanzania's largest and
most important harvest indicated that Tanzania had suffered a
virtually nationwide crop failure because of erratic and poorly
distributed rains.
</P>
<P>
The WFP move is a response to the appeal made by Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa Monday to western donors to provide
emergency food aid to Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
