<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Major Gas Generator Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- One of the gas turbine
generators which broke down earlier at one of the major power
stations, the Ubungo power station, in Dar es Salaam has been
repaired.
</P>
<P>
The repairs were completed early this week by an expert
brought by the suppliers of the turbines, the managing Director
of the Tanzania Electric Supply Company (TANESCO), Baruany
Luhanga told the local press Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Luhanga said, the completion of the repair works does
not mean the end of power rationing under which between 15 to 20
percent of Dar es Salaam region's requirement is being shed.
</P>
<P>
"We want to run all the gas turbines at Ubungo for 24 hours so
that we can avoid intensifying load shedding but the problem is
money to buy fuel to run the turbines," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "The four gas turbines at the Ubunga power station
consume a lot of fuel and our customers, government Ministries
plus their departments and parastatal organizations, hold 30
billion shillings (47.6 million US dollars)."
</P>
<P>
"Unless the government of our customers pays us it will be
very difficult for TANESCO to run the gas turbines and other
generators up country which depend on fuel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing has been imposed in Tanzania since September
8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
