<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Hit by Slump in Capital Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is suffering from
declining growth in private capital inflow, making it the second
worst level of inward investment in sub-Saharan Africa after
Gabon's, the East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The capital inflow fell 42 million U.S. Dollars in the past
decade in the eastern African country, the report quoted the
latest World Bank's Global Economic Prospects document as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenya's economic deterioration went back to 1991 when
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) cut its
economic aid after the government refused to implement economic
and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
A majority of sub-Saharan African nations have instituted its
sponsored economic reforms as a condition for getting economic
aid from the multi-national financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
While the Kenyan economy now is still struggling on its
recovery path, the IMF suspended 205-million-Dollar aid package
to the country on July 31, saying Kenya has not done enough to
end corruption and to conduct reforms demanded by the IMF and
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is asking the Kenyan authorities to restructure
parastatals like the Keny Posts and Telecommunications
Corporation and the Kenya Power and Lighting Company before
having them privatized.
</P>
<P>
The bank is also insisting on transparency and accountability,
especially in the Goldenberg scandal, which robbed the country of
several hundred millions of dollars in fictitious gold exports
and wants those involved to be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government showed willingness to negotiate with
both the IMF and the World Bank to resolve the outstanding issues
to pave way for the resumption of IMF aid program.
</P>
<P>
Among the key issues is the streamlining of the Kenya Revenue
Authority (KRA) to make it independent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka, Tribal Leaders Agree on Peace Deal to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and
tribal leaders have agreed upon a peace deal to end the
decades-old insurgency in southern Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT),
which will be signed in the next meeting, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"We have formulated a draft treaty and agreed to sign it at the
next meeting after discussion with my compatriots," said Shantu
Larma on Wednesday night, who is leading the delegation of the
Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), the political
wing of the armed rebels in the CHT.
</P>
<P>
However, Shantu Larma did not disclose when the next meeting
would take place.
</P>
<P>
He also did not speak anything about the terms and reference of
the draft accord on a permanent solution of the two-decade-old
problems in the ethnic strife-torn hill tracts.
</P>
<P>
Reading out a written statement on behalf of both sides, he
said that the ceasefire, which is still holding after several
renewals since 1992, had been extended upto December 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
Chief Whip and Chairman of the National Committee on CHT Hasnat
Abdullah, head of the government delegation, was standing at the
left of Shantu who said that the statement had the concurrence of
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)
Chairperson Khaleda Zia in a statement on the same day cautioned
against signing any agreement on CHT against the interests of the
nation and its people.
</P>
<P>
The former Prime Minister said the press reports on withdrawal
of army camps from the CHT created concern among the people.
</P>
<P>
Such steps would render the country's security fragile and
endanger life and property of the non-tribal people residing in
the area, about one-tenth of the territory of Bangladesh, she
added.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the signing ceremony would be
held within the next couple of months because it would need time
to formulate the final document.
</P>
<P>
The positive outcome came from the sixth round of talks
initiated by the present government to hammer out a formula of
restoring peace in the southeastern resource-rich hilly region,
bordering India and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist guerrillas had been fighting for autonomy in the
CHT area since early 1970s, that reportedly claimed the lives of
nearly 20,000 people, including troops, and drove 50,000 tribals
into refugee camps in the Indian state of Tripura.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
