<HEADLINE> Chilean Soccer Players to Countinue Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chilean soccer players'
union said on Wednesday that strike would be continued until two
clubs reinstated player who were sacked for joining the protest.
</P>
<P>
Union president Carlos Ramos said the basis for an agreement to
end the strike had been reached with the two provincial clubs
Coquimbo Unido and Osorno.
</P>
<P>
Players staged the strike at the weekend to draw attention to
alleged inadequate labor laws and dismal working conditions.
</P>
<P>
Though weekend matches went ahead with clubs fielding youth
teams, Sunday's Chilean championship was turned into a farce.
</P>
<P>
National team coach Nelson Acosta said he was worried the
strike could leave his players short of match practice in the
run-up to a crucial World Cup qualifier at home to Peru in October.
</P>
<P>
The two countries were the leading contenders to take the last
remaining South American place at the World Cup finals to be held
in France next year. 
</P>
