<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Optimistic About Future of Global Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), said today he
was fully confident of the good future of the world's economy, and
 also praised the on-going economic reform in China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Hall here this morning, Camdessus said all members of
the IMF would work hard for the good prospect of the global
economy in the coming few years.
</P>
<P>
He cited the following as the reasons behind his confidence in
the global economy:
</P>
<P>
-- All the countries of the Asian-Pacific Region have responded
 in a right way to challenges and can unite in efforts to make
their economy better;
</P>
<P>
-- Though there have appeared a financial crisis in Southeast
Asia, the whole world "goes forward to our goal";
</P>
<P>
-- The European Monetary Union (EMU) not only can "start on
time" in 1999, but also "have all the potential to be a very
positive development" for Europe and the international monetary
system;
</P>
<P>
-- The IMF would help and push forward the liberalization of
an orderly capital flow;
</P>
<P>
-- The second-generation economic reforms, particularly in the
Latin American countries, may succeed;
</P>
<P>
-- The countries eager to change their economic systems have
basically completed the transition and may keep the tendency of
their economic growth;
</P>
<P>
-- And China and its special administrative region Hong Kong,
under the "one country, two systems" concept, may help each other
in the economic development.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus applauded the results of the economic reform under
way in China and its economic growth, describing them as "very
impressive."
</P>
<P>
In response to questions from reporters, he said: "What I hear
from the orientations from the 15th Congress of the Communist
Party (of China) is encouraging." "They are putting the finger on
what must be one of the most essential challenges for (China) in
coming years," he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also expressed his readiness to provide help to
China in entering into the world's economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that the world is still witnessing some
facts that inflation may expand, some economic organizations are
trying to be enlarged and unemployment issues exist particularly
in Latin America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus also stressed the need for all the nations in the
world to unite in making the global economy better.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
