<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economy Inches Up in First Eight Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) from January to August
maintained the same level as last year, ending the plunge that
started in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production is up 1.4 percent compared with the same
period last year and witnessed a 3 percent hike in August, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An increase in production can be seen in nearly every
industrial department. The recovery in the auto industry is
impressive with a rise of 13.8 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's auto industry, once on the verge of ending production,
has successfully saved itself from these dire conditions. The
production of cars gained 260 percent, trucks 270 percent, motors
73.2 percent, and buses 16.7 percent, the statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
The minimum living expenses went down to 418,000 rubles (76
U.S. dollars) in August from July's 427,000 rubles (78
U.S. dollars). The average monthly income of the employed
population in the first eight months of this year reached 916,000
rubles (156 U.S. dollars), 20 percent up from the same period last
year, sources said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, the unemployment figure was 6.57 million,
which included the officially registered figure of 2.158 million,
and accounted for 3 percent of the economically independent
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
