<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Senior Party Leader G.M. Singh Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Ganesh Man Singh, the
senior leader of the Nepali Congress (NC), died early this morning
after a long illness, state-run radio said. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
For years, Singh had suffered from such chronic ailments as
hypertension, urinary track problem, diabetes and neurological
problems.
</P>
<P>
He just returned from India on September 11 following a
one-and-a-half-month treatment.
</P>
<P>
Singh worked actively against the Rana autocracy in the 1940s,
but he is best known for his role in eliciting the full support of
the leftist forces for the people's movement launched in 1990
against the Panchayat, or partyless system.
</P>
<P>
The people's movement forced King Birendra to abolish the
Panchayat system and establish a multi-party democracy under a
constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Singh was the first Nepalese to receive the U.N. Human Rights
Award. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
