<HEADLINE> Bangkok Offers Cash Rewards for Hospitalizing Lepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bangkok metropolitan
administration has offered to give a cash reward to volunteers who
bring lepers to hospital in a bid to wipe out the disease in the
city, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Bangkok Governor Kajit Choopanya Wednesday said the city
authorities will reward volunteers with 250 baht (about seven U.S.
dollars) for bringing each new leper to hospital for treatment,
The Nation reported.
</P>
<P>
They will also be rewarded with 500 baht (about 14 dollars)
further after the completion of treatment for each patient, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The cash reward measure is part of the Bangkok city
authorities' latest efforts to encourage the public to participate
in the health campaign to eradicate leprosy in the city by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has about 45,000 lepers, but only 2,772 needed to be
hospitalized, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The disease currently is under control in the country, the
newspaper stressed. The average infection rate is 0.45 per 10,000
of the population, but Bangkok is twice the national average.
</P>
</TEXT>
