<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Coordinate With Neighbors to Control Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will cooperate and
coordinate with Malaysia and Singapore in controlling the forest
fires in Sumatra and Kalimantan, which have caused thick haze
spreading to the two neighboring countries, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation will be made a priority to be taken to control
the fires," State Minister for Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja
said last night after attending a meeting of ASEAN environment
ministers being held here.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with Malaysia and Singapore, Sarwono said,
cloud-seeding would be made directly upon the spots of fire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Singaporean Minister for Environment Yeo Cheow Tong,
who is attending also the meeting, said Singapore would help make
the cloud-seeding and provide a satellite picture to detect the
forest situation in Sumatra and Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will provide meteorological data, weather forecasts,
feasibility studies and air quality index to support the
implementation of cloud-seeding, Malaysian Science, Technology and
Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng Ding said.
</P>
<P>
At least 300,000 hectares of forest, mostly in Sumatra and
Kalimantan, have been destroyed by fires in Indonesia this year.
</P>
<P>
The haze caused by the fires has reached an unhealthy level
here and in Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Officials here said about 20 million people are in danger of
respiratory problems due to the thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
The haze has also caused the delay of 800 flights and at least
seven boat collisions on central Kalimantan's Mahakam River in the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's meeting, Indonesia also proposed the setting up
of a regional command post for environmental information to
anticipate unpredictable environmental problems, sources at the
meeting said today.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, which was opened Tuesday by President
Soeharto, is being attended by representatives from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), which groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts from Japan, Canada, the United States and
Germany are attending.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
