<HEADLINE> ADB Offers New Loan for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has offered to extend an additional one billion US dollar
loan to fund the restructuring of Thailand's capital market and
help maintain the country's economic development drive.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Ministry Permanent Secretary Sukpachai Pisitvanich
said on Wednesday that the ADB's 10-year structural adjustment
loan would carry an interest rate of seven percent.
</P>
<P>
This time the ADB will not use its own money but will seek
lines of credit from other funding sources, said Sukpachai.
</P>
<P>
The new loan offer is in addition to the 1.2 billion dollars
the ADB contributed to the 17.2 billion international rescue
package arranged by the International Monetary Fund last month.
</P>
<P>
The ADB's first loan would primarily be used to streamline
Thailand's manufacturing and social sectors.
</P>
<P>
A Finance Ministry source said the ADB's additional loan
illustrated the importance the bank places on capital market
development and the developmnent of new instruments such as
futures, hedging and debt instruments to meet the country's
economic growth.  
</P>
