<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Has 80,000 Blind People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- About 80,000 people are
blind in Nepal and every year 16,000 more turn blind, according to
local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Blindness has been a major problem for the poor and rural
people in Nepal, whose population stands at 21 million, the
reports said, quoting a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
Cataract is the main cause of blindness for adults, while night
blindness resulting from deficiency of vitamin A is the main
reason behind children's blindness, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
Every day one child turns blind and another dies from blindness
in Nepal, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the blind can be cured through general
treatment or surgery, the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
The world has nearly 17 million blind people caused by
cataract, the survey added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
