<HEADLINE> Supply of Homes to Increase in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will see a rising
supply of unoccupied or second-hand homes during the second half
of this year, as more mortgagees will lose their homes to banks
due to the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Thai Farmers Bank Research
Center available today, the prices of the homes will fall further
beyond 20 percent during the coming months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The trend will expand into the next year as consumers' incomes
also are being affected due to salary cuts or layoffs, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government Housing Bank earlier estimated that there
will be 334,000 previously-owned homes for sale in Bangkok in
1997, up 12.5 percent from last year, and about 42.5 percent of
the total will be unoccupied homes.  
</P>
