<HEADLINE> Social Efforts To Help Unemployed In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 18 (Xinhua)-- Seven universities in east
China's Anhui province have sponsored free training courses for
laid-off workers to improve their work skill.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the efforts taken in the province to help those
unemployed find jobs.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has adopted a series of preferential
policies to help laid-off workers, including the stipulation that
either of the husband or wife should be helped to reemploy if both
of them were laid off.
</P>
<P>
In addition to setting aside special fund for the purpose, the
government has decided to exempt for a year the industrial,
commercial and other taxes for those self-employed.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises with good economic performance, opened their doors
wider to laid-off workers if they want to hire new workers, and at
least one third of whom would be unemployed ones. This is the case
not only in Hefei, capital of the province, but also in other
major cities, such as Wuhu and Bengbu.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, all social sectors have involved
themselves in the project. Scientific and technological
institutions, urban neighborhood committees all place it as a high
priority to introduce jobs for the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Though statistics are not available, the efforts of the whole
society in this regard are believed to be effective in solving the
unemployment problem. local officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
