<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Police Warn of Camouflage Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police have warned
the public that small daily utility items such as hair brushes
could turn out to be sharp knives in the hands of underworld
elements, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some of these dangerous weapons were disguised as key tags,
fountain pens, hair brushes and toy pistols, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said that a hair brush of the person seated next to you
on a bus could be a well-concealed weapon.
</P>
<P>
While nothing can be done about such things, police warned the
public to be on alert as they could be attacked suddenly.
</P>
<P>
At some check points in Colombo, the capital city, police have
already tracked down several such weapons during their routine
checks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Growth Means Opportunity for World: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China's rapid economic
growth will be an opportunity for, not a threat to the world
economy, the World Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
To avoid losses to everybody, China's accession to the World
Trade Organization is imperative, the bank said in its "China
2020" report released here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Once China's accession to the WTO is completed, trade relations
will become easier to handle and China's engagement with its
trading partners in a multilateral setting will strengthen
dialogue and encourage cooperation, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"If China's trading partners were to raise barriers to its
exports and China were to retaliate, the losses to everybody could
be large," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The opening of China's economy is an integral part of its
economic reform and a central element in its growth. Between 1978
and 1995, the value of exports and imports as a share of GDP
tripled and China became the world's second-largest recipient of
foreign direct investment after the United States.
</P>
<P>
By 2020, China could be the world's second largest exporter and
importer, and its consumers may have a purchasing power larger
than all of Europe's, the report predicted.
</P>
<P>
China's international integration is important to the rest of
the world as its trading partners will benefit from exporting to
its "vast and largely untapped markets", the report said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, foreign investors will be interested in China's sea
of skilled and disciplined workers, it added.
</P>
<P>
Industrial countries will benefit unequivocally from China's
rising demand for capital- and knowledge-intensive manufactures
and primary products and from significant terms of trade gains,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Only their labor-intensive manufacturing will face a squeeze,
but much of that structural change would have happened anyway,
with or without China," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank held that among developing countries
the effects of China's integration will depend on how much they
trade directly with China and how much they compete in third
markets.
</P>
<P>
Countries that trade heavily with China will gain
significantly, the report said, adding that low- and middle-income
countries that are close competitors with China will experience
some terms of trade losses, "but their total trade will keep
growing and perhaps their world market share of labor-intensive
manufactures as well". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Ratings For Thai Financial Firms Downgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The New York-based ratings
agency, Standard and Poor's, has downgraded the credit ratings for
seven Thai financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Among the seven are Bangkok Bank, Thailand's largest commercial
bank, and a few other large banks, such as Thai Farmers Bank and
Siam Commercial Bank.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank's credit ratings for foreign currency and local
currency had both been cut to BBB from A minus.
</P>
<P>
Thai Farmers Bank saw its ratings for both categories lowered
to BBB minus from BBB, and to BBB minus from BBB plus,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Siam Commercial Bank saw reductions to BBB minus from BBB plus
for both its foreign and local currency ratings.
</P>
<P>
Standard and Poor's predicted that non-performing loans in
Thailand's banking system would rise to at least 15 percent of
total loans next year as asset quality deteriorates.
</P>
<P>
The non-performing loans stood at 8.15 of the total at the end
of June, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency warned the banks' asset qualities would worsen into
next year and said a further downgrade could not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans currently exceed 30 billion U.S. dollars,
with much of it provided to property developers, who are now
unable to repay their debts as a result of property oversupply.
</P>
<P>
The agency predicted the bad loans would continue to mount
before peaking in the latter part of fiscal 1998 (October 1,
1997-September 30, 1998), since the real estate sector "is in a
significant slump" and would not improve in the short term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
