<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB on China's Economic Growth in Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The rapid growth of China's
economy over the next quarter-century is clearly possible as China
has some real advantages, the World Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
In its "China 2020" report released here this morning, the
World Bank said that China's high savings rate, relative
stability, large domestic market, and record of reform bode well
for future growth.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the needed savings rate and productivity growth,
China shall maintain the momentum of reforms and skilled
macroeconomic and sectoral management, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It said that China's Ninth Five-Year Plan and its Fifteen-Year
Perspective Plan, which focus not just on the future pace of
growth but also on the entire direction of development, have laid
out the government's approach to achieving rapid and sustained
growth well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China's Five-Year Plan for 1996-2000 targets the growth of the
gross domestic product (GDP) of eight percent a year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the first year of the plan, GDP growth reached 9.5
percent. To achieve the plan target by 2000, China will need to
grow by an average of 7.6 percent a year over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
By the standards of recent years, such growth does not seem
unduly ambitious, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report pointed out that China needs to deepen
its reforms and maintain stability to achieve a stable
macroeconomic environment and financial system, which will enable
savings to be channeled to their most productive uses.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government has a responsibility to
manage the change of the structure of the labor force, which will
accompany the growth.
</P>
<P>
The report said that even if China's savings rate declines from
around 40 percent to a still-robust 35 percent over the next ten
years, while productivity growth fades slightly, to a more modest
1.5 percent a year, its GDP growth would be 8.4 percent a year
between 1996 and 2000 and would average 6.6 percent over the 25
years until 2020.
</P>
<P>
By 2020 per capita income in China would be approaching those
of Portugal today but would still be less than half those in the
United States, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Industry will continue to account for a much larger share of
GDP and agriculture is expected to grow at about the same rate as
it has in the past, the said.
</P>
<P>
Services are expected to be by far the most dynamic sector of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong growth in the past decade, the share of services
in China's GDP is still well below that of a typical low-income
country.
</P>
<P>
This share could change dramatically over the next 25 years as
China acquires the characteristics of middle-income market
economies.
</P>
<P>
A key element in China's growth scenario is the transformation
in the composition of the labor force, the report noted. The
transformation should be viewed as an opportunity, not a threat.
</P>
<P>
China's surplus labor is one of its greatest
resources. Efficiently handled, it will provide a powerful impetus
to growth, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Able to Meet Challenges Ahead, Sustain Rapid Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China can meet the
challenges ahead and sustain its rapid growth in the coming decades,
said a report released here today by the World Bank a few days
before the opening of the World Bank/International Monetary Fund
Annual Meetings.
</P>
<P>
In the 161-page "China 2020", a special report of the WB/IMF
Annual Meetings devoted to the host country, the World Bank highly
praised the economic achievements China has made so far and
expressed strong optimism about the country's future development
after scrutinizing every aspect of its economy.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said that the two historic transitions China
has been experiencing from a command economy to a market-based
one and from a rural, agricultural society to an urban,
industrial one, have so far been "spectacularly successful".
</P>
<P>
China is the fastest-growing economy in the world, with per
capita incomes more than quadrupling since 1978. In two
generations it has achieved what took other countries centuries,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Swift growth and structural change, while resolving many
problems, have created new challenges concerning employment,
inequality, poverty, environment, and periods of macroeconomic
instability.
</P>
<P>
"China can meet these challenges and sustain rapid growth," it
asserted, adding that although the difficulties ahead should not
be underestimated, neither should China's strengths -- relative
stability, a remarkably high savings rate, a strong record of
pragmatic reforms, a disciplined and literate labor force, a
supportive Chinese diaspora, and a growing administrative
capacity.
</P>
<P>
"These strengths have driven China's growth for the last two
decades of this century. They could do the same in the first two
decades of the next," it said.
</P>
<P>
To nurture these strengths and use them effectively, the World
Bank suggested, reforms must develop in three related areas:
</P>
<P>
First, the spread of market forces must be encouraged,
especially through reforms of state enterprises, the financial
system, grain and labor markets, and pricing of natural resources;
</P>
<P>
Second, the government must begin serving markets by building
the legal, social, physical, and institutional infrastructure
needed for their rapid growth;
</P>
<P>
Finally, integration with the world economy must be deepened by
lowering import barriers, increasing the transparency and
predictability of the trade regime, and gradually integrating with
international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In summary, the report said that the past two decades have
seen China's sustained, rapid modernization unlike in any other
period in the country's long history. The next two decades
promise more of the same.
</P>
<P>
"The huge risks that China faces could yet take the shine off
this potential. But with resolute leadership at home and
statesmanlike policies from the world's industrial powers, China
can overcome these challenges," it asserted.
</P>
<P>
The report said that one-fifth of humanity would then have
within its grasp the power to break free of the shackles of
poverty and underdevelopment and accomplish what could become the
most remarkable economic transformation the world has ever seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
