<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB: China in Midst of Historic Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The first transition, from a rural, agricultural society to an
urban, industrial one, is remarkable because of China's vast size,
 its past control of urbanization and unprecedented speed of its
industrialization, said the WB report "China 2020: Development
Challenges in the New Century" released here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The second transition, from a command economy to a market-based
 one, has also been unique with a combination of experimentation
and incremental reforms, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank attributed China's rapid growth during the past
two decades to the interplay and synergy between these two
transitions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy expanded more than fourfold in the past 15
years. Between 1978 and 1995, real gross domestic product (GDP)
per capita grew at the blistering rate of 8 percent a year and
lifted 200 million Chinese out of absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also noted that the benefits of growth have been
 widely shared among China's country-size provincial
economies. Although the coastal provinces grew faster than average
at 9.7 percent a year, the other provinces also fared well.
</P>
<P>
Another noteworthy feature of China's growth since the
beginning of reform in 1978 is its reliance on productivity
growth. Relative to other rapidly growing Asian economies, China's
 growth has been less dependent on volume increases in inputs of
capital and labor, the World Bank report said.
</P>
<P>
China's remarkably rapid growth has been driven by four
factors: high savings rate, structural change, pragmatic and
incremental reforms as well as agriculture, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
China's savings rate, averaging 37 percent of GDP between 1978
and 1995, is among the highest in the world. "Savings, as much as
growth, is China's real economic miracle," said the report.
</P>
<P>
It seems China has the capacity to meet any challenges facing
its economy given the country's strengths -- relative stability, a
 remarkably high savings rate, a strong track record of pragmatic
reforms, a supportive Chinese diaspora, and a growing
administrative capacity, the World Bank report said.
</P>
<P>
"These strengths have driven China's impressive growth in the
last two decades of this century," said the report. "They will be
equally necessary for rapid, sustainable growth in the first two
decades of the next century."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
