<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Offers Suggestions for China's Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today urged
China to further separate the roles of government and markets and
clarify rights and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
A special report released by the World Bank here today said
that the separation and the clarification will help China lay the
foundations for sustained rapid growth and improve the quality of
people's life.
</P>
<P>
The report, "China 2020," said that the past 18 years in China
have underscored the importance of markets for growth and
prosperity, but the country's transition from a command to a
market economy is incomplete.
</P>
<P>
Many parts of the Chinese economy still have an undesirable
blurring of governmental and commercial functions, which creates
conflicts of interest within government and ultimately could harm
the economy, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that China further its efforts to boost
revenues, expand intergovernmental transfers in revenues from
richer provinces to the poorer ones and build transparent,
responsive fiscal institutions.
</P>
<P>
On the reforms of the state enterprises, it said that there is
little disagreement in China about the need to reform state
enterprises and financial system, noting that the challenge is to
introduce the reforms while maintaining rapid growth and economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report said that rather than reforming all state
enterprises at once, China's central authorities are focusing on
1,000 large state firms and on plans to invigorate them and make
them the core of modern enterprises.
</P>
<P>
It said that a key element necessary for the invigoration of
these 1,000 enterprises is an improvement in their governance,
especially in two areas: clarity on rights to assets and
assignment of liabilities among owners (the government), managers,
and creditors; and organizational structures that provide a
reasonable balance of interests among owners, creditors, and
managers.
</P>
<P>
The report also called on the government to improve the
efficiency and competitiveness of the 1,000 large enterprises, for
many of them will be exposed to international competition once
China joins the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
On the subject of transforming the banking system, the report
said that how the banking system evolves over the next 25 years
will hinge on the success of these reforms.
</P>
<P>
It said that transforming the state banks into genuine
commercial banks is crucial if China is to avoid a major bank
insolvency and if market forces are to shape the allocation of
financial resources in China.
</P>
<P>
The most important policy change required is a reduction in
government influence over the allocation of loans, it added.
</P>
<P>
Reform of interest rate policy will be an essential but
treacherous feature of China's financial development, it said,
adding that the Chinese government has already taken steps in the
right direction by reducing the number of officially determined
interest rates, introducing treasury bill auctions, adjusting
interest rates more than in line with inflation and initiating
open market operations.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the financial sector has been the soft underbelly
of China's reforms. It is the sector most vulnerable to shocks.
The authorities must be as relentless in their pursuit of reforms
in this area of the economy as they have been in others.
</P>
<P>
On establishing the rule of law, the report said that China has
made considerable progress in developing legal norms that
correspond to the needs of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it said, much remains to be done. It may take decades for
the rule of law to establish a firm foothold in China.
</P>
<P>
One remedy is to develop the legal profession and the next will
be to improve legal education.
</P>
<P>
To flourish, markets need a background of macroeconomic
stability, the report said, adding that in future the government
faces the more difficult task of maintaining macroeconomic and
financial stability by using indirect, market-friendly measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
