<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Maintains Steady Lead in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Main opposition leader Kim
Dae-jung continues to lead his four major rivals in almost all of
the popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
Although official campaigning has yet to get under way, it is
the first time in South Korean history that an opposition
candidate has taken the lead in opinion polls for a presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest opinion poll released Wednesday by the
Dong-a Ilbo newspaper and Han'gil Research, Kim Dae-jung, the
veteran opposition leader of the National Congress for New
Politics (NCNP), is supported by 29.7 percent of voters in a
five-way competition that includes Governor Rhee In-je of Kyonggi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Rhee garnered 24 percent, followed by ruling New Korea Party
(NKP) candidate Lee Hoi-chang who received 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rhee, who lost the ruling party's nomination to Lee in July,
left the party Saturday and announced his own bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Cho Soon, who is now president of the small opposition
Democratic Party (DP), came in fourth with support from 13 percent
of the survey respondents. Kim Jong-pil, leader of the second
opposition United Liberal Democrats (ULD), won 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, who also topped the latest public polls conducted
by the Joong'ang Ilbo, Hankyoreh 21, and Sisa Journal news
weeklies, has topped the popularity polls since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the Joong'ang survey showed that 50.6 percent of
the respondents believe the December presidential poll will mark
the first-ever transfer of power from a ruling party to the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
However, because none of the candidates enjoys an overwhelming
lead, experts say several possible alliances among candidates make
the situation far from clear.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung has been trying to persuade Kim Jong-pil to
support him since June. Negotiators from the two sides are
discussing which Kim should represent the two parties in the
election.
</P>
<P>
Kim of the ULD also seeks to join hands with ruling NKP
candidate Lee Hoi-chang.
</P>
<P>
In this context, Lee may also try to push for an alliance with
former Seoul Mayor Cho Soon to turn the election into a showdown
between him and Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts see a high possibility of an alliance
between independent Rhee and Cho in that both are calling for a
generational change in politics and the end of the political
domination of the so-called three Kims, referring to President Kim
Young-sam and opposition leaders Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the analysts point out that both Rhee and Cho have
almost the same support base; they both take away votes from the
ruling party and Kim Dae-jung's NCNP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
