<HEADLINE> Russia Joins Paris Club of Credit Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Vice
Prime-Minister Anatoli Chubais signed an agreement here today with
Christian Noyer, president of the Paris Club of creditors, on
Russia's joining of the organization.
</P>
<P>
Chubais said after the signing ceremony that the agreement is
very important in the Russian political and financial arena,
adding that it affirms Russia's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will hold an equal status with world industrialized
countries afterwards," said Chubais.
</P>
<P>
The Club, also known as the Group-10, which includes the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands,
Canada, Belgium, Sweden, Switzerland and Luxembourg, exists to
coordinate the strategy of creditor nations with regard to debtors.
</P>
<P>
Russia holds credits inherited from loans made by the former
Soviet Union worth 140 billion U.S. dollars and gains some 200
million U.S. dollars of interest every year. Chubais said he
hopes that membership will make Russia garner 500-700 million
U.S. dollars of interest payments per year. 
</P>
