<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Investors Plough Into Ukrainian Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has become the
third largest foreign investor in Ukraine following the United
States and Germany, and Dutch investors have brought a total of
32.5 million U.S. dollars into the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a great deal of Dutch telecommunications
investment in Ukraine. They came in at the beginning, and the
investment is continuing," explained Dutch Embassy Counselor Onno
Eldernbosch.
</P>
<P>
Overhauling communications infrastructure in Ukraine requires
major capital investment. The joint venture, the UTEL, among the
Netherlands, Germany, the United States and Ukraine has to spend 5
million dollars on each of the digital international telephone
exchanges installed in places from Lvov (western Ukraine) to
Donetsk (eastern Ukraine). The Dutch phone company PTT Telecom
owns 10 percent of the UTEL.
</P>
<P>
"The equipment is all very expensive, and you can't just
install part of it. Once you decide to improve telecommunications
anywhere, you're committed to major expenditures," said UTEL
President Olexy Marynchuk. He estimates the company's overall
investment in the Ukrainian market will reach 150 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We began here in 1992, and I can't see the flow of Dutch money
stopping any time in the near future," he said.
</P>
<P>
PTT Telecom is also helping to fund Ukrainian Mobile
Communications (UMC), a joint venture of cellular telephone. The
UMC is setting up base stations, relay stations and transmission
units necessary to make a modern mobile phone network operate in
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
"It's a massive project and we're here in Ukraine for a long
term goal," UMC Marketing and Advertising Director Jakov
Schleicher said. He disclosed that the UMC has already invested
150 million dollars, and the total investment in 1997 will amount
to 57-60 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dutch businessmen has shown great interest in this country
despite perceived red tape.
</P>
<P>
"We are patient and flexible. We're guests here and must play
by Ukrainian rules," said ING Bank office director Robert
Grant. The ING, one of the Netherlands' largest banks, has
recently opened an office in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Shell International Petroleum Company will likely to invest up
to 1.5 billion dollars in Ukraine, despite slow progress in its
negotiations with Ukrainian authorities on building oil pipelines
across the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
