<HEADLINE> Peru's Exports Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Peru's exports in the first
eight months of this year reached 4.61 billion U.S. dollars, an
18.4 percent increase over the same period last year, an official
organization said.
</P>
<P>
Traditional product exports, including coffee and fish oil,
rose by 13 percent from a year ago to 4.3 billion dollars,
according to Prompex, an institution in charge of promoting
exports.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports in this period reached 310 million
dollars, up 34 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Prompex said exports have been doing well despite climatic
variations affecting most of the productive sectors of the country.
</P>
<P>
Prompex General Manager Antonio Castillo said the organization
is considering special programs to help agricultural exporters
tackle the problems caused by the "El Nino" phenomenon. The
government is also studying the possibility of increasing credit
for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Prompex is promoting new export products such as giant corn,
olives, tomatoes, asparagus and citrus fruits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
