<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central American Countries Sign Easy Entry by Air Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Four Central American
countries -- El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Nicaragua --
have signed an agreement to ensure free entry via air transit for
their citizens into each other's countries.
</P>
<P>
Vice foreign ministers from the four countries, members of the
so-called CA-4 group, signed the deal on Tuesday in San Salvador,
which takes effect on November 1 and is expected to benefit nearly
20 million Central American people.
</P>
<P>
The contract enables nationals of the four countries to enter
any other signatory nation by air after producing their identity
cards.
</P>
<P>
The CA-4 group will hold seminars in October to train
immigration personnel and airlines officials on the new
procedures. Every airport in the four countries will set up a post
in charge of services for Central American citizens.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica, another Central American country, did not
participate in the program, saying it fears an influx of citizens
from neighboring and poorer countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Official Advocates Permanent War Crimes Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy believes that a permanent
international tribunal should be set up to try war criminals,
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said today.
</P>
<P>
He told a conference on unpunished crimes and human rights
violations in the Sicilian city of Siracusa that "only through a
permanent tribunal can peace go in step with justice and the
fundamental role of law in the new world order be affirmed."
</P>
<P>
He said that a diplomatic-level meeting will be held in Rome
next summer to pave the way for the establishment of such a
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
United Nations members favor a new permanent tribunal to judge
genocide, massacres and war crimes but some of their proposals may
virtually kill its ability to function. Legal experts from more
than 100 countries have been struggling to reconcile a myriad of
conflicting views.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new court will be separate from the International
Court of Justice at The Hague, which deals with disputes between
nations.
</P>
<P>
The new tribunal could be built on the four ad hoc tribunals
that have prosecuted heinous crimes since 1945. They include the
Nuremberg and Tokyo tribunals that tried war criminals of World
War Two, a tribunal set up in The Hague during the Yugoslav civil
war, and another one set up in Arusha, Tanzania, after the 1994
genocide in Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0259 </DOCNO>
