<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Shield Banks From Bad Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank is
fast-tracking a plan to hike banks' loan loss reserve rate from
1.3 to two percent as part of measures to prevent mounting
defaults, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed plan is intended to protect the country's banking
system from excessive defaults, which triggered the current
financial turmoil sweeping the Southeast Asian region, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Amid the currency woes, Thai baht, Indonesian rupiah, Malaysian
ringgit, Philippine peso and Singapore dollar have devalued since
early July.
</P>
<P>
The peso broke the mark of 33 to the U.S. dollar in Wednesday's
trading due to unconfirmed reports that the country would cut
further banks' liquidity reserve rate which had already been
slashed from eight percent to six percent.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to be caught unprepared," a Philippine Central
Bank official explained why the bank is mulling over the plan to
raise the loan loss reserve rate.
</P>
<P>
The monetary authorities are also looking into an amendment to
the General Banking Act to allow bank-creditors to go after a
debtor using a loan for other purposes than originally intended,
the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
