<HEADLINE> World Champion Hill Leaves Arrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- World Champion Damon Hill has
departed from Arrows, the Formula One team confirmed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
To replace Hill, Arrows has signed Finla Salo to join the
team's other current driver Pedro Diniz of Brazil for the 1998
season, said director Tom Walkinshaw.
</P>
<P>
Hill, 37, joined the little-known Arrows team this year after
winning the drivers' championship last season with Williams. He
struggled to make an impact this season but lied in a miserable
13th place in the standings with seven points.
</P>
<P>
Salo, of Tyrrell-Ford this season, was 17th in the standings
with two points.
</P>
<P>
Hill, looking for a more competitive drive next season, has
been linked with a move to the Prost and Jordan teams. After
Prost said it had broken off talks with Hill, the world champion
was more likely to move to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Arrows said money was the main factor in letting Hill go. Hill
was paid a reported 4.5 million pounds (7.2 million U.S. dollars)
by Arrows this season but has reportedly been seeking an increase
for next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
