<HEADLINE> China's Township Enterprise Becomes GM's Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- General Motors recently
ordered 75,000 universal joints for automobiles from the Wanxiang
Group, a township enterprise in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The contract for the order, which came after ten rounds of
negotiations between the two sides, was GM's first with a Chinese
township company.
</P>
<P>
GM's order means that Wanxiang's products will be used on the
assembly line of the world's largest auto maker, said Chairman of
Wanxiang board Lu Guanqiu.
</P>
<P>
Wanxiang's products were exported to the international
maintenance market in the past, according to Lu, who was once
featured on the cover of the Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, Wanxiang earned 61
million US dollars of foreign exchange from exporting universal
joints to 34 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a third of Wanxiang's 200 million yuan-worth of
monthly products are exported through its sales branches in the
United States, Britain, Mexico, Brazil, Canada and Venezuela.
</P>
