<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan's Private Sector Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of
individually-owned businesses increased by 56,800 in southwest
China's Yunnan Province in the first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The province now has more than 6,400 private enterprises, a
rise of 16.6 percent compared with the end of last year, according
to statistics.
</P>
<P>
"Since the policy of reforms and opening-up was introduced in
the late 1970s, Yunnan's private sector has been growing fast,"
said Fei Jia, an official of the Provincial Administration for
Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the non-state sector has not yet
developed enough, restricting the overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the combined output value of Yunnan's private
sector accounts for only two percent of the total industrial
output value.
</P>
<P>
To give impetus to the private sector, the province has been
pursuing a series of preferential policies on loans, taxation,
registration, and land use.
</P>
<P>
In line with a regulation, the private businesses run by
laid-off workers can enjoy tax-free treatment.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the effort, Yunnan's private businesses generated
contributed an aggregate output value of 7.6 billion yuan (910
million US dollars) in the past five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
