<HEADLINE> China Beats Saudi Arabia in Asian Men's Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The showdown between
undefeated powerhouses China and Saudi Arabia was decidedly
one-sided as China emerged with an 84-62 victory on Wednesday at
the Asian Men's Basketball Championship in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Who would win was never in question once the game began
although Saudi Arabia led briefly by scoring the first basket.
</P>
<P>
China built a 36-22 lead with four minutes to go in the first
half and went to the locker room at halftime with a commanding
52-27 lead.
</P>
<P>
Hu Weidong scored the most of 19 points for China that boasted
of four players with double digitals as Gong Xiaobin added with
18, Wang Zhizhi with 14 and Liu Yudong with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
For the hosts, Adil Al Jehani scored 16 points, and Ali Al
Sanahani added with 9 points.
</P>
<P>
Saudi coach Pat Stewart tried to will his team to victory and
was shouting instructions at his players from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
"China's too big, too strong and too good," coach Stewart said
after the game, "They are the best team in Asia. We must improve
some more to win against China."
</P>
<P>
Stewart has coached the team for the past two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
"It was a big game. This is the game we've been preparing for,"
he said. Saudi will face Japan in the semifinal action on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The key to winning against Japan, with or without injured
Kenichi Sako, is shutting down Michael Takahashi, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
China will face South Korea in other semifinal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
