<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Promotes Tianjin Overall Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade accounts for
more than 60 percent of the local GDP in Tianjin, north China's
largest port city, and has contributed greatly to the advancement
of the city's overall economic development.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume of 8.3 billion US dollars in 1996
accounted for 60 percent of the local GDP, a dramatic rise of 30
percent on 1992.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade for the first half of this year reached 4.1
billion US dollars, with imports and exports rising 12.9 percent
and 20.9 percent respectively on the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city's favorable geographical location has helped increase
the country's exports, and also encouraged a large number of
overseas companies to invest in the port city.
</P>
<P>
The city has so far attracted more than 15 billion US dollars
of foreign investment in 10,000 enterprises. Major transnationals
such as Motorola, Samsung, Toyota and Otis are involved in the
city's electronics, automobile manufacturing, machinery and
petrochemical sectors.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded businesses have accounted for more than half of
local exports in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Over 190 of the world's top 500 industrial enterprises have
invested in the city, and a number of multinational companies have
established production bases to serve markets in the Asia-Pacific
Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
