<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Congress as Seen by Ordinary People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Zhenjiang,
Jiangsu Province, are paying special attention to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's call to the nation at the 15th Party
National Congress to fight corruption, as the composer of the
popular "Song On Building a Clean Government" is a hometown boy.
</P>
<P>
Xie Jianhua, a 42-year-old worker at the city's post office,
wrote the tune in 1994 after the 14th Party National
Congress. China's renowned musician He Luting later revised the
piece.
</P>
<P>
It was first sung by the city's 130,000 Party members, and
later caught on in the rest of the province. Now, nearly 30
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have requested
tapes or lyrics of the song, considering it a good educational
tool for improving the Party's work style and promoting ethical
and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
When interviewed by Xinhua, Xie took from his pocket a
newspaper clipping of the text of Jiang's report, and read aloud
the part about Party officials serving the people heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
"Every word of this passage strikes the chord in our hearts, and
we will make a greater effort to promote the building of a clean
government," Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the city has launched campaigns to
encourage leading officials to build up a good public image. This
effort has greatly improved the morale of society, said Zhang
Kemin, secretary of the Zhenjiang City Party Commission for
Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
"The report got to the core of our problems, and more
importantly, it defines a fundamental way to eliminate graft,"
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang sang part of the song: "People's cadres must bear in mind
that every post holds a corresponding duty;they must work in the
interests of the people and bring happiness to them; and they can
only win trust and confidence of the people by serving them
wholeheartedly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
