<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Helicopter Crashes in Bosnia, 12 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. helicopter crashed over
a fog-shrouded hill in Central Bosnia today, killing 12 people,
including a senior German diplomat.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said all the passengers -- five Germans, five
Americans, a Briton and a Pole -- were all killed.
</P>
<P>
The four members of the Ukrainian crew survived the accident,
said Kai Eide, head of of the U.N. mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
German diplomat Gerd Wagner, deputy to the international High
Representative to Bosnia, and a U.S. official, David Kriskovic,
working as the deputy commissioner of the U.N. International
Police Task Force, were among those killed.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said the death of Wagner
was a major loss to the Bosnian peace effort.
</P>
<P>
"I can only hope that the parties to the Dayton Peace Agreement
commemorate his loss of life by redoubling their efforts to
achieve the goal of lasting peace," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter, a Soviet-built Mi-8, ran into dense fog while
flying through a valley near Fojnica, 50 kilometers northwest of
the capital Sarajevo, Eide said.
</P>
<P>
"Visibility was cut to a minimum. The pilots attempted to
ascend, but before they reached a safe altitude the helicopter hit
a mountainside," Eide said.
</P>
<P>
"The glass nose of the helicopter was shattered, allowing the
crew to escape through the front. Although injured in the crash,
the crew attempted to assist the passengers but were hindered by
fire and thick smoke."
</P>
<P>
One passenger was found alive and evacuated by NATO soldiers
but later died of his injuries.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said
they had no reason to believe the crash was anything other than an
accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
