<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian Conservation Foundation has decided on a
radical change of direction following an internal review that
identified a serious lack of public engagement with environmental
issues, such as the greenhouse emission debate, uranium mining and
wood chipping.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The union movement in Australia has warned that the
Australian government's attempts to rein in union power in two key
sectors, the coal-mining and stevedoring industries, may lead to a
national blockade of shipping and spread to workers in other key
industries.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's two largest health funds will increase their
premiums by up to 20 percent on October 1, or up to 144 U.S.
dollars, for more than three million people, offsetting the
federal tax rebates intended to encourage more people to take out
private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australian bond interest rates yesterday plunged to record
lows in the wake of one of the lowest U.S. inflation figures in a
decade, as expectations mounted in local markets of a further cut
in official rates. 
</P>
