<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Purposes, Principles of UN Charter Inviolable: China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Purposes and
Principles of the United Nations Charter and the spirit of
Resolution 2758 were inviolable, stressed Ambassador Qin Huasun,
permanent representative of China to the United Nations, today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the General Committee of the 52nd session of the
General Assembly, Ambassador Qin said, "Having been defeated for
four consecutive years, a very small number of countries, in
disregard of the norms of international law, the United Nations
Charter and the resolution of the United Nations General Assembly,
have put forward once again this year the proposal on the
so-called Taiwan's `return to the United Nations,' in which they
openly requested review of Resolution 2758 of the General
Assembly."
</P>
<P>
"The proposal distorts facts in a brazen attempt to make use of
the augustness of the organization of the United Nations to carry
out activities aimed at splitting a sovereign state and creating
`two Chinas,' `one China, one Taiwan,' or `one country, two
governments,'" said Qin.
</P>
<P>
Qin said this had not only seriously encroached upon China's
sovereignty and grossly interfered in its internal affairs, but
also willfully trampled upon the Purposes and Principles of the
Charter and Resolution 2758 of the General Assembly, at which
the Chinese government and people expressed their strong
indignation and condemnation.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly oppose the inclusion of item 159 of the provisional
agenda in the agenda of the current session of the General
Assembly and hope that members of the General Committee will
uphold justice, safeguard the Purposes and Principles of the
Charter and the spirit of Resolution 2758 and support the position
of the Chinese delegation," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Qin said, "Taiwan has been an inalienable part of the Chinese
territory since ancient times. The 1943 Cairo Declaration and the
1945 Potsdam Proclamation once again affirmed China's sovereignty
over Taiwan. To date, 159 countries have established diplomatic
relations with China. They all recognize that there is but one
China in the world, that the Government of the People's Republic
of China is the sole legal government representing China in its
entirety and that Taiwan is part of China."
</P>
<P>
Qin said, "In 1971, the General Assembly adopted at its 26th
session by an overwhelming majority the historically significant
Resolution 2758. This resolution clearly and unequivocally
recognizes that the representatives of the Government of the
People's Republic of China are the only lawful representatives of
China to the United Nations and that the People's Republic of
China is one of the five permanent members of the Security
Council and decides to restore all rights of the People's
Republic of China in the United Nations and immediately expel the
representatives of Taiwan from the place which they unlawfully
occupy at the United Nations and in all the organizations related
to it."
</P>
<P>
Qin stressed that this resolution had accurately grasped the
essence of the question of China's representation at the United
Nations, and the restoration of the lawful rights of the People's
Republic of China and the expulsion of the Taiwan authorities from
the United Nations were two indivisible aspects of the same
question.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the resolution had affirmed the "one China" principle,
thus settling once and for all and in a just manner the question
of China's representation at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The resolution which had reflected the Purposes and Principles
of the Charter as well as the desire of an overwhelming majority
of countries of the United Nations was a victory of justice, Qin
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Committee Decides Not to Consider Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The General Committee
of the 52nd session of the General Assembly of the United Nations
today decided not to consider the question of the so-called
"representation" of Taiwan at the current session.
</P>
<P>
It has been for five consecutive years that the General
Committee foiled Taiwan's plots aiming at splitting a sovereign
country and creating "two Chinas," "one China, one Taiwan" or "one
country, two governments."
</P>
<P>
On July 14, 1997, Nicaragua and a very small number of other
countries addressed a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
in which they requested inscription on the agenda of the 52nd
session of the General Assembly of an item on the so-called
"necessity to review Resolution 2758 of the General Assembly of
the United Nations due to fundamental change in the international
situation and two governments co-existing across the Taiwan
Straits."
</P>
<P>
The General Committee comprises the President of the General
Assembly and the Vice-Presidents of the Assembly, and the chairs
of the six Main Committees.
</P>
<P>
The General Committee considers the provisional agenda and the
supplementary list, considers the requests for the inclusion of
additional items on the agenda, allocates items to committees, and
submits its report for the approval of the Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Reaps Budgetary Surplus in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government reaped
a budgetary surplus of 800 million dollars (576 million US
dollars) in July, the Finance Department said today.
</P>
<P>
July is the third consecutive month in which the government
recorded a surplus.
</P>
<P>
This figure represents a net improvement in the government's
budgetary position of 2 billion dollars (1.44 billion US dollars)
from July 1996.
</P>
<P>
In July, the government's budgetary revenues were up 8.8
percent, while program spending declined 8.1 percent. And public
debt charges were down 8.7 percent, the department said in its
monthly Fiscal Monitor release.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this fiscal year, the government
has reported a surplus of 300 million dollars (210 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
While in the same period last year, it recorded a deficit of
6.5 billion dollars (4.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
This turnaround came largely from an improving economy and the
restraint measures introduced in the past two years, the
department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
