<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Worried Over German Economic Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank today
voiced worries that the country's economic recovery could not
sustain, saying political factors were hampering an increase in
investments vital to stimulate economy, which has been all the
time dependent on exports.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report for September, the Bundesbank stressed
that investments were the key to ignite the second stage of
economic recovery just as export was in the first stage.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, "political uncertainties concerning important
reform projects" were leading to a wait-and-see attitude of the
potential investors.
</P>
<P>
The report believed that without increased investments, the
country's problems of high unemployment -- currently at an
"unacceptable" level of more than 4 million -- and weak
consumption could not be overcome.
</P>
<P>
It hailed the signs of revival in domestic demand and noted
that the increased spending by private households applied only to
food and beverage items, but not to durable goods.
</P>
<P>
The decisive factor which would trigger a long-term recovery in
consumption would be an increase "in investments at home through
which additional jobs would be created, in turn increasing
disposable income," it said.
</P>
<P>
But such a far-reaching improvement in investments was not in
sight, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank in the report warned against any overestimation
of the current economic situation in Germany, saying the problems
facing Germany as an economic base were far from being solved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
