<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Pakistan Shocked over Terrorist Killing of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- While expressing their
profound shock and grief over the killing of five Iranian
trainees, Pakistan leaders were confident that the terrorist
attack would not affect the country's friendly ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Five Iranian National Civil Aviation trainees, who came here in
August for two months of training, and their Pakistani driver were
killed by three unidentified gunmen this morning at Rawalpindi,
the sister city of the Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
According to local police, the Iranians were attacked on their
way from the Kamra aeronautical complex, some 70 kilometers west
of Rawalpindi, to the Civil Aviation Dhamial Camp in the city.
</P>
<P>
When their van reached the busy Chour Chowk, three unidentified
motorcyclists appeared on the road and sprayed bursts of
Kalashnikov bullets on the van, smashing the windscreen of the
vehicle and killing the driver and two of the trainees on the
spot. The other three succumbed to their injuries on their way to
hospital.
</P>
<P>
High officials of district administration rushed to the spot as
soon as they heard about the incident and police have sealed off
all the main points of the city to look for the culprits.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani Defense Ministry is now making arrangements for
sending the bodies of the trainees back to Iran on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the shooting, Iran lodged a strong protest
against Pakistan over the killing and demanded swift arrest and
punishment of the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Expressing their profound grief over the killings, Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, President Farooq Leghari and Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan assured that the government would give
exemplary punishment to the culprits.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan leaders also expressed their confidence that
bilateral relations between Pakistan and Iran would not be
adversely affected by the terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between Pakistan and Iran rest on the solid
foundations of our Islamic faith, a shared cultural heritage and
coincidence of interests on the major issues of our time," Sharif
said in a message addressed to Iranian President Sayed Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that no dastardly act of terrorism can affect
our time-tested friendship which serves the larger interests of
the two brotherly peoples," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said in his condolence message that Pakistan remains
committed to a close cooperative relationship with Iran and shall
work closely with the Iranian government in defeating the
nefarious objectives of the criminal terrorists.
</P>
<P>
So far no group or individuals have claimed responsibility for
the killing. According to unconfirmed reports, police have
arrested two persons suspected of involvement in the killing.
However, analysts here believed that some sectarian groups may be
behind the tragedy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Fund Targets More Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Africa
Investment Fund (COMAFIN) has identified 11 more
projects for funding which will be forwarded for approval by the
COMAFIN Investment Committee in London next week.
</P>
<P>
COMAFIN Chief Executive Jeffrey Goddard told the Zimbabwe News
Agency today that the projects are in Uganda, Ghana, Tanzania,
Cameroon, Kenya, Namibia and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fund has already approved investment
totalling 7.3 million U.S. Dollars in four projects in Tanzania,
Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The COMAFIN is the first of the funds set up under the
Commonwealth Private Investment Initiative (CPII).
</P>
<P>
The initiative was launched in 1995 by Commonwealth finance
ministers and endorsed by their heads of government to channel
long-term commercial investments to support expanding privatized
or privatizing companies, new ventures and small or medium-sized
private sector businesses in the developing countries of the
association.
</P>
<P>
The main investors are the Commonwealth Development
Corporation, the Development Bank of Southern Africa, and the
governments or their investment agencies of Botswana, Brunei,
Malaysia, Singapore, South Africa and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
