<HEADLINE> Companies Join to Bring Multimedia to European Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- 13 information and
communication companies will work together to bring multimedia to
schools in Europe, the European Commission (EC) said today.
</P>
<P>
They are working together within the framework of an action
plan, entitled Learning in the Information Society, in order to
enable schools to cooperate through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The companies, including Apple Computers, British Telecom,
Belgacom, Microsoft and Oracle, have formed the European Education
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
The group is aimed at offering concrete help to specific needs
in the educational sector, such as the connection among schools,
the equipment maintenance, training teachers and developing
multimedia content.
</P>
<P>
The partnership will become even more operational with the
creation in early 1998 of a foundation grouping private and public
undertakings and educational authorities from the member states of
the European Union (EU), said the EC, the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
One of the main objectives of the action plan is to strengthen
the cooperation between public and private undertakings in
bringing multimedia into schools.
</P>
<P>
The plan was initiated by Edith Cresson, the EU commissioner
for research, education, training and youth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
