<HEADLINE> Cypriot Spokesman on Clerides-Denktash Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot government
spokesman said here today that the upcoming talks between Greek
and Turkish Cypriot leaders on security issues will aim at finding
concrete solutions to matters concerned to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Manolis Christofides said that during the talks between Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash, each side will present particular security concerns.
</P>
<P>
However, he said President Clerides' proposal for the
demilitarization of the Cyprus island is "a fundamental aspect
which could be included in the security matters to be discussed."
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.N. will not put forward any proposals
during the talks and there is no agenda for the talks.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Clerides, U.N. Resident Representative
Gustave Feissel said here today that he expected the first meeting
to take place next week and "if possible early next week." The
U.N. official is expected to have a meeting Thursday with Denktash
to fix the exact date of the Clerides-Denktash talks.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on security talks between two Cypriot
communities' leaders was announced Monday by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright during a stop-over in Cyprus after a tour
to the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
It was the result of a shuttle-diplomacy by newly-appointed
U.S. State Department's Special Coordinator for Cyprus Thomas
Miller during his four-day visit to the island following the
failure of two rounds of U.N.-led direct talks between Clerides
and Denktash in July and August.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that only Clerides and Denktash will
be present at the talks, in the presence of Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreement reached aims at creating an
atmosphere which will facilitate negotiations between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides on the fundamental aspects of the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops took over the northern
third of the island in the wake of a short-lived coup seeking
union with Greece by some Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
