<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan, Xinjiang Delegates Give Press Conference (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Asked to comment on the remarks about Tibet made by Frank Wolf,
a Republican congressman from the State of Virginia, USA, Chen
Kuiyuan, secretary of the CPC Committee of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, said Wolf spread lots of rumors on Tibet after sneaking
round in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
"His remarks are groundless," he said.
</P>
<P>
For example, Wolf said there were "more Chinese in Lhasa than
Tibetans," though he had never been to Tibet before, nor did he
know how many people of the Han nationality there are in Tibet.
"On what grounds did he say there are more Hans than Tibetans in
Tibet?" Chen asked.
</P>
<P>
Wolf alleged that Tibetan buildings had been buried among the
Han-style buildings. Chen said Lhasa is undertaking the
modernization drive, and hence there is little difference between
the buildings of the Han-style and that of the Western style and
Tibetan style.
</P>
<P>
On Wolf's remarks that there is no religious freedom, Chen said
the Lamas have been engaged in religious activities in Tibet's
monasteries every day. All religious people lead an ordinary
religious life.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, some people outside China have wantonly
fabricated sensational rumors to vilify modern Tibet and pour
dirty water on the Tibetan people in order to mislead the public
opinion. "This has led to confusions and misunderstanding of
Tibet, and Wolf's remarks are a case in point," the regional Party
chief said.
</P>
<P>
On relations between different ethnic groups, Abdul'ahat
Abdurixit, chairman of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, said
people of different ethnic groups are working hard to develop,
build and safeguard the border regions.
</P>
<P>
So far, people of various ethnic groups have established new
relations of equality, mutual help and unity. Both the Han people
and other ethnic groups cannot do without each other.
</P>
<P>
However, there are only a handful of people who are creating
contradictions and carrying out activities to split the
motherland. "The overwhelming majority of the people in Xinjiang
love socialism and safeguard the reunification of the motherland,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
