<HEADLINE> Land Mines Kill 11 ECOMOG Soldiers in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Eleven west African peacekeepers
have been killed by land mines in Sierra Leone and five others died of
undisclosed illness in Liberia while carrying out their mission,
according to the Nigerian military authorities.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the 16 soldiers, said to be Nigerians, had been flown
to Nigeria for burial with military honors, Godwin Ugbo, Director
of Defense Information, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 11 soldiers were killed by land mines planted by the Sierra
Leone junta which seized power in a coup on May 25, instead of losing
their lives in recent crossfire with the junta army, the defense
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The soliders were under the command of the headquarters of the West
African Peacekeeping Force (ECOMOG), which has succeeded in ending
Liberia's civil war and is in Sierra Leone to enforce economic embargo
ordered by sub-regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the embargo, aimded at forcing the junta out
of power, is hitting hard on Sierra Leone, leading to the spread of
malnutrition and diseases and shortage of daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Children's Fund has called for the supply of
humanitarian goods to the country, while a group of Sierra Leonean
traders have also appealed relaxation of the blockade so that goods
needed for day to day living can be imported.
</P>
<P>
Confrontation between ECOMOG troops and soldiers loyal to the junta
has also intensified the situation in the country, particularly at
port areas in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local residents have reportedly fled the areas with
their belongings for fear of renewed exchange of fire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
