<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Peasants Urged to Use Natural, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian peasants today
were urged to use natural and artificial fertilizers together to
boost agricultural productivity as well as keep the natural
resources intact.
</P>
<P>
The call came from Mengesha Bekele, General Manager of the
Ethiopian National Fertilizer Industry Agency at a workshop here.
</P>
<P>
Mengesha also called on concerned bodies in the country to
encourage peasants to use natural and artificial fertilizers
together and improve soil fertility and reduce the country's
dependence on fertilizer imports.
</P>
<P>
He said, the natural fertilizers obtained from chickens' and
cattle manure as well as decay of dead leaves enrich plant
nutrients without causing environmental air-pollution.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that fertilizer consumption in Ethiopia has
steadily increased during the past 20 years. However, during the
period from 1994 to 1996 the price of sulphur and urea rose 40
and 50 percent respectively, he added. 
