<HEADLINE> 12 Killed in A UN Helicopter Crash in Bosnia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 17 (Xinhua)-- A senior international mediator
from Germany, Gerd Wagner, was among the 12 people killed in a
crash of a UN helicopter in central Bosnia early today, German
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Wagner, 55, was the deputy to Carlos Westendorp of Spain, top
civilian mediator in charge of implementing peace in Bosnia.
Speaking fluent Serbo-Croatian, Wagner assumed the post just three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter with 16 people on board hit a mountain some 15
kilometers northwest off Sarajevo after leaving the Sarajevo
airport at about 9:15 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The people were heading for Bugojno to check conditions for the
return of refugees on behalf of the Bosnian peacekeeping forces
SFOR, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
Five Germans, including Wagner, five U.S. citizens, one British
national and one Pole were killed. The four Ukrainian crew members
survived the tragic accident, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kinkel, the pilot of the helicopter said that the
plane had flown into an unexpected dense fog. And when it emerged
from the fog, the mountain was right in front of the plane into
which it crashed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
