<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Take Steps for Possible Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's cabinet
today approved several measures to counter the expected effects
of the El Nino phenomenon, which could cause severe drought in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
A severe drought was expected from November to March 1998, and
its effect on South African economy needed to be mitigated by
pre-emptive disaster management, Constitutional Development
Minister Valli Moosa told a press conference in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
An Inter-Ministerial Committee for Disaster Management had
been set up to coordinate the activities of the government with
regard to the El Nino phenomenon, Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet demanded the provincial governments take
steps to ensure that special institutions be established to deal
with the El Nino and other disaster related incidents, stressing
the Department of State Expenditure must ensure that an emergency
fund be made available.
</P>
<P>
A white paper on a pre-disaster policy would be tabled in
parliament in January next year.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet had also recommended that all departments and
provinces should develop and implement action plans to mitigate
the expected El Nino effects.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of agriculture and water affairs would announce
their plan of action soon, Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet had also approved an urgent ministers meeting of
the Southern African Development Community to address the
consequences of El Nino phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
