<HEADLINE> Baril Appointed Canada's Chief of Defense Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Lieutenant-General Maurice
Baril has been promoted to the rank of general and appointed chief
of the defense staff, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien
announced today.
</P>
<P>
Prior to today's appointment, General Baril was commander of
the Land Forces Command.
</P>
<P>
"General Baril has had a distinguished career in the Canadian
Forces, with assignments ranging from serving in Cyprus to that of
military advisor to the Secretary-General of the United Nations,"
said a release from Chretien's office.
</P>
<P>
Chretien chose Baril over acting chief Vice-Admiral Larry
Murray partly because of the latter's name was tainted by fallout
from the Somalia scandal, and partly because of strong military
backing for Baril, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Murray will leave the military and become a civilian associate
deputy minister in November, Chretien said in the release.
</P>
<P>
The new chief of defense staff, who will turn 54 next week, got
a high profile last year when he led a multinational relief
mission to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
While in charge of the land forces in the past two years, Baril
criticized army leadership at all levels, and earned a reputation
as a straight-talking reformer.
</P>
<P>
He convened a surprise news conference in July last year to
announce that 34 soldiers had been implicated in misconduct,
drunkenness and black marketeering while they were deployed in
Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
