</P>
<P>
Addressing commanders of Iran's Islamic Revolution's Guards
Corps (IRGC), Khamenei said "those claims have lost credibility
in the eyes of the world's public."
</P>
<P>
Khamenei, also commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces, said
that Iran's strength does not emanate from inter-continental
ballistic missiles or nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"If such arms were source of real strength, the governments
possessing those would have long succeeded (in) imposing their
will over the world," he was quoted by the agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei also enumerated the U.S. failures in international
arena, its failures to suppress Muslim nations including the
Palestinians and many unsuccessful attempts to contain Iran's
progress as further evidences of ineffectivity of the arms.
</P>
<P>
The supreme leader termed the rank and file of the IRGC as
"children of the Islamic Revolution (in 1979)," emphasizing the
importance of adherence to piety both individually and within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
He further called for piety and strict devotion to the
doctrines of Islam as the source of Iran's strength and welfare
for its people.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammad
denied Iran's attempts to build nuclear weapons alleged by Israel.
</P>
<P>
At the same day, Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi rejected
recent allegations by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
that Iran was the main source of tension in the Middle East
because it was seeking weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
At his meeting with the commanders of the IRGC today, Khamenei
also attacked the United States for offering unconditional support
for the Israeli regime in conflicts with the Palestinians, noting
that "the Palestinian nation and its flag will remain alive,
instead, the Zionist regime and its staunch supporters will
disappear from the face of the earth."
</P>
<P>
The IRGC, Iran's main and largest fighting force, was formed by
Iran's clerical government shortly after it came to power in 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC has an air wing of its own, and had its own navy until
it was merged with the regular naval forces a few years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
