<HEADLINE> British Newspapers to Tighten Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Editors of Britain's leading
newspapers today agreed to exercise more self-restraint in the
wake of the death of Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with the editors, chairman of the Press
Complaints Commission (PCC) Lord Wakeham demanded a tighter code
of practice after paparazzi photographers were accused of
contributing to Diana's death in a car chase.
</P>
<P>
"We support Lord Wakeham's calls for wide-ranging and rigorous
reforms and recognize that there is a shared determination to rid
our publications of practices which we all deplore," said David
English, editor-in-chief of the Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
Wakeham said the PCC would discuss revisions to the
self-regulatory code next week with the aim of clamping down on
the use of intrusive photographs taken by freelance paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
The press watchdog would also aim to tighten newspaper
guidelines on questions of privacy, harassment, treatment of
children and intrusion into grief, he added.
</P>
<P>
British newspapers have promised either not to print paparazzi
photographs of Diana's sons, Prince William and Prince Harry, or
else not to breach their privacy with unauthorized photographs.
</P>
<P>
Despite repeated calls for a press law, the British media
remains self-regulating. Legal experts say it would be hard to
draw up and enforce a law that distinguishes between people's
right to privacy and the right of the press to investigate matters
of public interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
