<HEADLINE> Egypt to Exempt Palestinian Students From Tuition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has decided to exempt
Palestinian students from tuition and registration fees in a
show of concern for the Palestinians, the Middle East News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif said today that
the Palestinian students' registration and tuition fees last year
stood at 2.132 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the exemptions will apply to the
offsprings of Egyptian women whether divorced, widowed, or whose
Palestinian husbands work in the Egyptian government and public
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The privilege will also be granted to those Palestinian students
whose parents permanently live in Egypt and wish to join the
Egyptian universities and institutions but can not afford to pay
their registration and tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
These students will be fully exempted from registration fees
that range between about 1,600 and 2,250 dollars a year for every
student and asked to pay only 10 percent of their tuition fees, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Ambassador here Zohdi el-Kodna
today praised the Egyptian move as "a courageous national
decision" that reflects Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
consistent support to the Palestinians living under the Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
He said education and culture is a vital part of the
Palestinians' future and an important weapon against Israeli
occupation. The Palestinian diplomat called upon other Arab
countries to follow Egypt's action.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has donated 10 million dollars to help ease the
plight of the Palestinians suffering under an Israeli closure
imposed following a double suicide bombing attack in Jerusalem on
July 30, which killed 17 people and injured 170 others.
</P>
<P>
The PNA lost between 5 million and 8 million dollars a day due
to the closure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
