<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Pakistan to Bring Assailants to Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today urged Pakistan to bring into justice the
assailants who gunned down five Iranian air force trainees in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also called on his Pakistan counterpart to do
everything possible to make sure that the assailants are
arrested and punished.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president described the Wednesday incident in
Pakistan city of Rawalpindi as "painful to the government and
people of Iran".
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the 54-year-old
president made the statement in a telephone call with Pakistan
President Sardar Farooq Ahmad Khan Leghari, who sent a cable of
condolence to his Iranian counterpart after the tragic incident
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Leghari assured Khatami that those who had committed the
killings could not adversely affect the solid relations between
Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to an early report, five Iranian air force trainees
were gunned down by unidentified terrorists in Rawalpindi as they
were proceeding to a training school in a car Wednesday
morning. Four were killed on the spot and the fifth died in
hospital later. Only one student survived.
</P>
<P>
The report said that, the bodies of the five Iranians are
to be flown to Tehran on board a Pakistan plane escorted by
a Pakistan official Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the incident, Iran's Foreign Ministry immediately
 summoned Pakistani Ambassador to protest against the
assassination and urged Pakistani government to arrest and punish
the assailants of the five Iranians.
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, Foreign Minister Gowhar Ayoub-Khan said his
government would do everything to trace and arrest the
assailants.
</P>
<P>
In another message to the Iranian president, Pakistan Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif offered his shock over the incident but
assured Khatami that such incidents would never affect relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Foreign Minister Gowhar Ayoub Khan also telephoned
Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister for Asia-Pacific affairs Mohsen
Aminzadeh today and condoled with him on the killing of the
five Iranians.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would go to every length in order
to identify and arrest the assailants of the five Iranians.
</P>
<P>
In Tehran Wednesday, the Islamic Revolution's Guards Corps
issued a communique on the occasion calling on the Pakistan
government to identify and arrest the killers of the five
Iranians.
</P>
<P>
It also recalled that the Iranians had several times before
been attacked by unidentified assailants in Pakistan, and warned
that the Pakistan government would better react logically to
the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
