<HEADLINE> Canadian Women Less Likely to Quit Jobs for Family, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Women working in Canada are
less likely to interrupt careers for family reasons, according to
the latest survey by Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
And those who take a break from paid jobs are more likely to
return more quickly than previous generations.
</P>
<P>
Better legal protection for things such as maternity leave, and
the importance of two-family income are the major reasons for the
social changes, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
"There will always be work interruptions, but the frequency and
duration of them is changing," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, Canadian women left paid employment for extended
periods and only one out of eight returned to work within two
years of leaving. In the 1990, 55 percent returned within two
years.
</P>
<P>
While women in the 1950s and 1960s often cited family as the
reason for quitting work, the pattern has changed significantly.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, fewer than half, or 47 percent, of careers breaks
were family related.
</P>
<P>
Economic reasons, such as layoffs, contract expiry, accounted
for 22 percent of women's work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
Of the women who left the workforce, the survey said 71 percent
returned to work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970918.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
