<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders Air Safety Review After Air Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen today ordered the military services to halt training
flights for 24 hours and review safety procedures following five
air crashes in four days.
</P>
<P>
"Perfection is impossible, but that is our goal for aviation
safety," Cohen said in a statement released at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the review may begin at any time during the week
starting at 7 a.m. EDT Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cohen noted that his directive will not affect operational
flights, such as those enforcing the no-fly zone over Iraq or the
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's instructions were delivered in letters to the civilian
leaders of the Army, Air Force, Navy and Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
The order was made in the wake of a series of air crashes
within a week.
</P>
<P>
Two Air National Guard fighter jets collided off the coast of
New Jersey on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An Air Force F-117A fighter crashed during a Maryland air show
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a Marine F-A-18D Hornet fighter jet crashed in North
Carolina's Pamlico Sound during a practice bombing run.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday a U.S. Navy F-A-18 crashed in Oman, killing the
pilot.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday a U.S. Air Force C-141 transport plane flying from
Namibia and carrying nine men crashed in the South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Monday urged Cohen to analyze
the crashes "to see if there is some pattern that would require
some sort of review by the Air Force." 
</P>
</TEXT>
