<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of prospective
jurors for the second Oklahoma City bombing trial are meeting with
U.S. District Judge Richard P. Matsch in Denver, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of a Federal Building in Oklahoma city on April 19,
1995, killed 168 people and injured hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
Coloradans from 23 counties will fill out a second
questionnaire, presumably asking for their feelings about the
death penalty, pretrial publicity and other issues in Terry
Nichols' trial which is slated to begin September 29, according to
a United Press International report.
</P>
<P>
This time the prospects will be quizzed about their knowledge
of the trial of Timothy McVeigh, the first suspect of the bombing,
which ended with the former Army sergeant convicted of all 11
counts and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, Nichols could also get the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
District court clerk James Manspeaker says about 750 initial
questionnaires of the 1,000 summonses sent out early this month
were filled out and mailed back. Some recipients had moved away
and their summonses were returned.
</P>
<P>
Individual questioning of jurors by prosecutors and defense
attorneys begins after opening statements in Nichols' trial in
Denver. 
</P>
