<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Rejects Land-mine Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday announced that the United States would not sign a treaty
banning anti-personnel land-mines, saying the accord would
endanger American troops.
</P>
<P>
"There is a line that I simply cannot cross, and that line is
the safety and security of our men and women in uniform," Clinton
said in his announcement.
</P>
<P>
the United States at the last minute tried to persuade a
conference in Oslo of more than 100 countries to modify a draft
treaty banning land-mines. It wanted an exemption that would let
the United States to continue to use the weapons on the Korean
Peninsula for nine more years because of what it called an
uncertain situation there.
</P>
<P>
But the Oslo conference rejected the U.S. proposal and went on
to approve the draft treaty on Wednesday. And the delegates to the
Oslo conference will reconvene on Thursday to formally accept the
draft. The actual signing is not expected until December.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, speaking at the White House, said he felt the Korean
exemption was necessary ato protect about 37,000 U.S. military
personnel deployed there.
</P>
<P>
Earlier White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters: "We
regret that the document emerging from Oslo... will not meet some
of the necessary precautions that the United states insists upon as
we make the transition to a landmine-free globe."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, however, said he was directing the Defense
Department to develop alternatives to land-mines as a gesture of
softening his position. "In short, this program will eliminate
all anti-personnel land-mines from America's arsenal" by 2006,
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
