<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Peace Activists Demonstrate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 300 Israeli and
Palestinian peace activists demonstrated this evening in disputed
Ras Al-Amud Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem, calling for
peace and an end to Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration, organized by Peace Now, a joint
Israeli-Palestinian peace movement, was held outside the two
buildings in the neighborhood which were occupied by 15 Jewish
settlers Sunday. The incident sparked a new crisis in the tense
Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
Holding placards reading "Save Peace," "Netanyahu Destroys
Peace," the demonstrators blasted Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for torpedo the hope for peace, and U.S. billionaire
Irving Moscowitz for trying to ignite a war between Israelis and
Palestinians by building the Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
Moscowitz, who bought the two houses and the adjacent area
where he intended to build 70 housing units to create a Jewish
settlement, visited Ras Al-Amud this afternoon, vowing that he
would never act to evacuate the settlers.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Minister for Jerusalem Affairs
Faisal Husseini and Israeli opposition Labor Party member Orren
Sahour made speeches during the demonstration. They demanded the
Israeli government take measures to evacuate the settlers in order
to save peace.
</P>
<P>
Calling for coexistence between Israelis and Palestinians in
Jerusalem, Husseini said the Israeli government must end the
provocation by ousting the settlers from Ras Al-Amud.
</P>
<P>
"We want peace now, we want a future and life, we want a
future for our children," he said. He called on peace-lovers from
both sides to join hands in working for peace.
</P>
<P>
Sahour stressed that Netanyahu must remove the settlers from
Ras Al-Amud, whom he accused of violating law and order.
</P>
<P>
"We want them out of the buildings, we want the continuation
of the peace process. And I hope we should continue with the
peace process ... peace with security can be made only with the
peace process and through negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The crowd responded to the speeches with loud applauses.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Hassan Zaqail, a Palestinian taxis station telephone
operator and a member of Peace Now, told Xinhua that he came to
support peace, adding there would be no peace with settlement.
</P>
<P>
Zaqail, who showed his right hand injuried by Israeli police
in a previous demonstration, said the houses belonged to his
grandmother but were sold by his cousins, who moved to Romania
now, to Moscowitz for a high price.
</P>
<P>
He said the settlers must leave the Palestinian land,
otherwise there would be Palestinian violence against the
provocation.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinians are waiting for the settlers to leave
of their own, and if not, they would be driven out by stones in
what he called a "war."
</P>
<P>
Over 100 Israeli police in anti-rioting gear were deployed
near the site to prevent possible outbreak of Palestinian
violence. Police helicopters continued hovering over the site to
guard against any disturbances.
</P>
<P>
The peace demonstration proceeded peacefully for about one
hour. But as a sign of the explosive situation, a group of
Palestinian protesters had moments earlier clashed with Israeli
police.
</P>
<P>
Some Palestinian youths threw stones at the police and
scuffled with them with sticks. During the clash, six
demonstrators were arrested and some injured by police. The group
was quickly overpowered and dispersed by the large presence of
Israeli police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
