<HEADLINE> UK Political Parties Cooperate Closely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair and
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown ushered in a new era of
political cooperation in Britain today by inaugurating a special
cabinet committee to explore issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time politicians from outside the ruling
party of the day had attended a cabinet committee since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see a new style of politics, and this is very much
part of it," said an aide to Ashdown. "But coalition is not what
this is about."
</P>
<P>
The new consultative committee, bringing together five Liberal
Democrats and six cabinet ministers, spent 90 minutes discussing
first-name terms government plans for reform of Britain's
unwritten constitution.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman in Blair's office said the two parties agreed to
cooperate closely on legislation to implement plans for home rule
for Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
Although the Labor Party won the general election on May 1 with
a huge 179-seat majority in parliament, Blair said that he was
setting up the committee to ensure maximum support for his
constitutional reform.
</P>
<P>
The ideological gap between Labor and the Liberal Democrats,
Britain's third-biggest party after the Conservatives, has
narrowed as Labor has moved to the center ground of politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
