<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers Calls for Help to Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Arab ministers of economy
today called for collective efforts to force Israel to lift the
siege on the Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and halt
the deterioration of their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Wrapping up the 60th meeting of the Arab League Economic and
Social Council, the ministers called upon the donor countries to
support the Palestinian people in reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed thanks to the Arab countries and Arab
institutions that offer assistance to the Palestinian people and
called for more aid in order to confront their present tough
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated the importance of enhancing
Arab-Palestinian trade relations, protecting production bases of
the Palestinian economy and limiting its dependence on Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) sustained daily
economic losses of 5 to 8 million U.S. dollars as a result of
Israeli blockade since a double suicide bombing attack hit
Jerusalem on July 30, in which 17 people were killed and over 170
others injured.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has donated 10 million dollars to help ease the plight of
the Palestinians and has decided to exempt Palestinian students in
Egypt from tuition and registration fees.
</P>
<P>
To canvass assistance for the frail Palestinian economy, PNA
President Yasser Arafat said he will expound the deteriorating
conditions inside the self-rule territories at the inaugural
session of the 108th Arab League Council meeting due to open on
Saturday in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's decision followed an Israeli announcement on Tuesday
that it would ease the closure of West Bank and Gaza reimposed
after September 4 triple suicide bombing in Jerusalem which killed
five Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
