<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Survey Finds Inflation Subdued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic growth
accelerated late this summer but inflation remained subdued, the
U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) said today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed's survey of its 12 districts showed a continuation
of the conditions -- solid growth and quiet inflation -- that have
restrained policy-makers from increasing interest rates since
March.
</P>
<P>
"Although some districts note signs of slowing in selected
sectors, about half the districts say their region's overall pace
picked up," said the survey, based on information collected before
September 8.
</P>
<P>
"Most regions are experiencing tight labor markets, recruiting
difficulties or growing labor shortages," it said. But two-thirds
said that is not translating into higher wages.
</P>
<P>
The report said that "with a few exceptions, prices for goods
are said to be moving very little, if at all."
</P>
<P>
The survey was released just two weeks before the U.S. Fed's
policy-makers meet to set interest rates on September 30.
</P>
<P>
However, in a speech in Pittsburgh, Fed board member Laurence
H. Meyer warned the economy "may already be operating beyond its
sustainable capacity."
</P>
<P>
He said that Fed policy "must be alert to the potential of a
developing upward trend in inflation."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) also warned
today in Hong Kong that the forces that have tamed U.S. inflation
are probably temporary. It said that "the continued surge in the
stock market and the strength of consumer and business confidence
suggest that the risk of overheating is still present." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
