<HEADLINE> US Says UN Chopper Crash Appears an Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that the crash of a United Nations helicopter in Bosnia that
has killed at least 11 people appears to be an accident.
</P>
<P>
"We have no reason to believe that the crash was anything other
than an accident," State Department spokesman James Rubin told a
regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, a U.N. spokesman said that at least 11
passengers were killed when the helicopter slammed into a hill in
a remote area in central Bosnia while four other passengers were
injured and one was still missing.
</P>
<P>
Gerd Wagner, a German envoy who is charge of trying to
implement the peace accord, was among those victims.
</P>
<P>
It was the worst accident involving international envoys in the
Balkans since April in 1996 when a plane carrying U.S. Commerce
Secretary Ron Brown from Tuzla, Bosnia, to Dubrovnik, Croatia,
crashed, killing Brown and 34 others.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously this is a very sad day. It points up the dangers
that diplomats and all others, including refugee workers, face in
Bosnia," Rubin told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
