<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Not to Exchange Ambassador Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish Foreign Ministry
spokesman said today that neither Turkey nor Iran has decided to
appoint ambassador to each other.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press briefing here, spokesman Omer Akbel
said that neither Ankara nor Tehran took any steps in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Iran expelled each other's ambassador after the
breakout of their disputes over sensative religious issues.
</P>
<P>
The dispute was triggered by former Iranian ambassador to Ankara
Muhammed Reza Baqeri who made a pro-Sharia (Islamic law) speech at
the commemoration of an anti-Israeli "Al-Quds (Jerusalem) Night"
gathering last February in the Turkish city of Sincan, 40
kilometers west of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Describing Iran as an important and friendly country in the
region, Akbel reiterated that Turkey is willing to strengthen
relations with Tehran so long as "some conditions are met."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been accusing Iran of supporting the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party and interfering in Turkey's internal
affairs over religious matter.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem is expected to meet with
his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi in New York where they will
participate in the forthcoming 52nd U.N. General Assembly session,
Akbel said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel sent a
special envoy to Tehran to express Turkey's desire to normalize
bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
