<HEADLINE> European Shares up on Benign US Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in
Europe all ended in the positive ground today, supported by a 4.8
percent drop in US August housing starts.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index had eased earlier in the day on British
unemployment and retail sales data which fueled speculation of
another interest rate rise.
</P>
<P>
However, the index moved back above the key 5,000-point level
once again later in the afternoon and ended up 36.7 points at
5,013.10, boosted by US housing data which showed the US economy
cooling and led to expectations that the Federal Reserve would
keep interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares climbed above the 4,000-level and
closed up 111.53 points or 2.86 percent at 4,010.48, underlined by
Wall Street's overnight strong gains.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that banks were among the biggest gainers as
takeover speculation simmered.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, shares finished slightly up, but off their
session highs on profit-taking and the Dow's failure to hold up to
its early gains, with the CAC-40 index 3.45 points higher at
2,944.0. 
</P>
</TEXT>
