<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel of Violating Signed Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jerusalem, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat said in Gaza today that building
a Jewish settlement in an Arab neighborhood of Jerusalem was a
clear violation by the Israeli government of the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Allowing the settlers to remain would violate the peace
agreements, he said. "We hope it will be solved very
quickly. Otherwise there will be a negative reaction," Arafat told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He made the comments in response to the move of 15 Jewish
settlers into Ras Al-Amud, an Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem,
Sunday, which triggered a new crisis in the tense
Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Queria, Speaker of the Palestinian Council,
issued a statement in West Bank city Ramallah, calling on the
Israeli government to take steps to remove the settlers from Ras
Al-Amud. He said the Netanyahu government bears full
responsibility for any dire consequences of the latest development.
</P>
<P>
Despite the presure from the Palestinian side, U.S. billionaire
Irving Moscowitz, who intends to build 70 housing units in Ras
Al-Amud to create a Jewish settlement, vowed that he would not act
to evacuate the settlers after visiting the houses this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's Supreme Court will hear a petition
Thursday filed by Moscowitz against the government for not
allowing him to start now the construction of the Ras Al-Amud
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Netanyahu held emergency consultations with
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Foreign Minister David
Levy to discuss the Ras Al-Amud dispute and the government's
response.
</P>
<P>
No details of today's inner Cabinet session was released. But
Netanyahu has made it clear days ago that he was opposed to the
actions taken by the settlers at this stage. However, he said that
the government has limited capability to remove the settlers
because they had acted "legally."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, it is expected that Netanyahu would likely
invoke the reasons for state security and public order in
blocking Moscowitz from starting the construction in Ras Al-Amud
at present moment so to avoid an escalation of the
Israeli-Palestinian tension.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Palestinians are demonstrating this evening in
East Jerusalem to protest against the Jewish settlement. The
Israeli police trying to disperse the procession clashed with the
demonstrators and arrested six of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
