<HEADLINE> Clinton Sees Encouraging Signs in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
said today that there are some encouraging signs in the Middle
East for reviving the moribund peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I have seen some encouraging signs in the last couple of days
that all the parties realize that they have special
responsibilities to get this thing back on track," Clinton told
reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on what encouraging signs he saw, but
administration officials cited such things as better
Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation in recent days, Israel's
partial return of tax and customs revenues it was withholding from
the Palestinians and lifting of the closure of West Bank towns.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also praised Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for
her trip to the Middle East, saying she had done "a superb job...
with difficult circumstance."
</P>
<P>
Asked what steps the United States would take in pushing the
peace process in the Middle East, Clinton said his foreign policy
team would "do everything we can to keep pushing this."
</P>
<P>
"We are going to do everything we can to try create the
condition in which they (the Israelis and Palestinians) can
succeed and to try to protect them from the downsides if they do
take risks for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the peace is for the parties there to make,
"and they have to have the vision and the courage and the strength
to do it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
