<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Expansion Should Now Take Priority Over Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Challenging a proposal made by
Paris, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said today that the
eastward expansion of the European Union (EU) should now take
priority over its internal reforms.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the remarks in an interview with the German
Suedwestfunk radio after France, along with Belgium and Italy,
submitted a paper to a meeting of the EU foreign ministers Monday
in Brussels stressing the need for further internal reforms and
integration prior to taking new East European members.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the EU reforms had already been discussed by the
last EU summit in Amsterdam in June, Kinkel said, "Now it's about
the next step, namely the expansion."
</P>
<P>
However, he also admitted that the accord reached at the
Amsterdam summit was only a provisional result which failed to
resolve key issues such as the proposed majority voting system and
the reform of the EU commission.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, we will continue to deal with all institutional
questions at the same time," Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel's remarks were made on the eve of the 70th Franco-German
summit which will be held in the eastern German city of Weimar
Thursday and Friday and will be attended by German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
